<2ND_LINE>AM-Busey Crash, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0754,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actor Gary Busey Critically Injured In Motorcycle Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Busey undergoing two-hour
operation, comment from manager. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `He was...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA16</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Gary Busey was in critical
condition Sunday with severe head injuries after losing control of
his motorcycle, authorities said.
   Busey, 44, of Malibu underwent two hours of neurosurgery Sunday
evening, said Ron Wise, spokesman for Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in
Los Angeles. He was then transferred to intensive care.
   ``He's in critical condition following a motorcycle accident at
about noon. He has extensive head trauma,'' Wise said.
   Busey's work as the doomed 1950s rock star in the 1978 film ``The
Buddy Holly Story'' earned him an Academy Award nomination. The
one-time rock 'n' roll musician, who like Holly was born in Texas,
performed his own renditions of Holly songs in the film.
   Busey's manager, Herb Nanas, said information regarding the
surgery's outcome wouldn't be available until Monday.
   No other vehicles were involved in the crash in Culver City, some
10 miles west of downtown Los Angeles, said police Sgt. Gary McEwen.
The weather was clear and the road was dry at the time of the crash.
   ``He was on his motorcycle and went down,'' McEwen said.
   The crash occurred at about 11:40 a.m., said police Sgt. Karin
Reagan.
   ``Our initial investigation showed that he lost control of the
bike, laid it down and was thrown off,'' Ms. Reagan said. ``He hit
the curb with his head and wasn't wearing a helmet at the time of
the crash.''
   In addition to his role as Buddy Holly, Busey has appeared in
films such as ``Big Wednesday,'' ``A Star Is Born,'' ``Lethal
Weapon,'' ``Carny'' and ``The Bear.'' He was a star of an ABC-TV
comedy series, ``The Texas Wheelers,'' in 1974-75.
   An HBO cable TV miniseries, ``A Dangerous Life,'' was shown a
week ago. He played a television reporter covering the revolution
that put Philippine President Corazon Aquino in power and ousted
Ferdinand Marcos. Last year, he won an ACE award for cable
television as best actor in a drama series for an episode of ``The
Hitchhiker'' on HBO.
   The actor was born and grew up in Goose Creek, Texas, and went to
college in Kansas and Oklahoma. He beat well-publicized drug,
alcohol and overeating problems that temporarily stalled his career.
   In an interview 2{ years ago, he said he had gotten off drugs,
chiefly cocaine, and had lost 55 pounds. He took up drugs in the
aftermath of his success with ``The Buddy Holly Story,'' he said.
   ``I was up for an Academy Award my first time out of the chute,''
he said in the interview. ``That breeds insecurity. ... How was I to
come up to those expectations again? I was wondering if I was a
flash in the pan.''
   He married Judy Helkenberg in 1969; they have a teen-age son,
Jake.
</TEXT>
