<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Gorbachev-Hall     12-04 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gorbachev-Hall,0671</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top U.S. Communist: Gorbachev Agenda Overdue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The melding of communism and democracy under
Mikhail S. Gorbachev is long overdue, America's top communist said
on the eve of the Soviet leader's visit.
   ``For years, I've been saying the socialist countries should move
in a democratic direction,'' said Gus Hall, general secretary of the
70-year-old Communist Party, U.S.A. ``There's no big threat _ they
can afford it.''
   ``It is true of any society ... Certain things get stuck and
changes don't take place corresponding to the new conditions. It's
necessary to shake up a society,'' he said. ``Socialism had reached
a level where some of the negative(s) had piled up. Somebody had to
provide a lead ... moving them to a higher state.''
   Glasnost and peace initiatives were among the topics on Hall's
mind as he and other Americans awaited Gorbachev's visit to New York
Tuesday through Thursday. The Soviet leader will address the United
Nations General Assembly and meet with President Reagan and
President-elect George Bush.
   ``I've met Gorbachev before he became general secretary and then
since,'' said Hall, 78, who has been employed full-time as general
secretary of the American communist party since 1959 and has run for
president four times since 1972.
   ``He's of a different generation and therefore, in many ways,
he's easier to deal with. He's very friendly and outgoing and easy
to talk to; if you express differences, it doesn't seem personal
with him,'' Hall said of Gorbachev. ``He's not afraid to try.
(Glasnost) calls for trial and error, and he seems to be very bold
in trying new ideas.''
   ``This is a historic moment in the socialist countries. They have
developed problems and they are correcting problems. They will
discard what doesn't work and keep what works. The Chinese are doing
a similar trial and error,'' Hall said in an interview Thursday. ``I
think much of it will stick. There's an experimentation with a
market economy and ... doing away with some of the centralization
that had taken place.''
   The Communist Party, U.S.A., advocates cooperatives and ``mom and
pop'' style, private enterprise, but eschews big corporations and
foreign involvement, said spokeswoman Carole Marks.
   Hall, who jokingly calls himself the ``big Red,'' said he sees no
contradiction in a communist advocating democracy, either here or in
the Soviet Union.
   ``There's no question that the more democracy, the easier it is
for people to fight for their rights. Like trade unions: the more
rights they have, the stronger they will be in fighting for wages
and so on,'' he said. ``There'll be some blurring of lines, but it
will not basically change the socialist concept.''
   In this country, ``our party has always stood for expanding the
democratic structure. ... Part of the electoral structure is very
undemocratic. We didn't run for president this year because the
restrictions were so severe it was hard to get on the ballot,'' he
said.
   The last time he did run, in 1984, Hall polled 36,386 votes which
was enough to beat out the Socialist Workers candidate but fell
54,418,689 votes short of Reagan.
   Despite his misgivings about the presidential election, Hall said
he thinks the Bush administration ``will not be quite as ideological
as the Reagan administration, but more realistic and practical.''
   ``The Bush administration will have to find some way of cutting
the expenditures. ... You can't be a first-rate power in the world
if you are a second or third-rate power at home and economically.''
   Marks said the United States has about 25,000 ``card-carrying
communists.''
   ``We're involved in the mainstream political life in this
country. We're accepted as the longstanding organization on the
left,'' she said.
   The group advocates creating a new political system for the
United States, but would not model it after the Soviet Union or any
other government, she said.
</TEXT>
