<HEAD>275 Told To Evacuate Briely When Dump At Sawmill Catches Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with evacuation warning lifted,
fire out. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `We have...'. DELETES penultimate
graf, now outdated.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MUNFORDVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire in a dump at a sawmill on Sunday
sent smoke and fumes through a nearby residential area, prompting an
evacuation warning that affected about 275 people before the blaze
was extinguished, authorities said.
   The warning was lifted at late evening after tests showed no
hazardous fumes, officials said.
   ``The fire is out,'' said Terri Belt, public information officer
for the Hart County Disaster and Emergency Services. ``The EPA has
been up there, has done the air tests and they have not found any
hazards in the smoke.''
   The blaze, believed to have begun Saturday, kept smoldering hours
after firefighters covered it with dirt Sunday afternoon, said Bill
Crabtree, coordinator of the state Disaster and Emergency Services
agency in the county.
   ``We have truck tires, plastics, wiring that's coated with
plastic, coated with rubber, big balls of nylon. Really, we don't
know for sure what's in there burning,'' Crabtree said.
   Fumes from the fire caused shortness of breath and burning eyes
to those exposed to it, Crabtree said.
   No one showed up for hospital treatment, however, said a
spokeswoman at Caverna Memorial Hospital.
   The material apparently had been covered with sawdust and logging
products at Anderson Forest Products, 3 miles north of Munfordville,
he said. Crabtree said he could not comment on whether anyone would
be cited for the dump, which he said was not legal.
   The blaze did not threaten any property ``except the property
it's on,'' he said. ``There's not buildings involved in it.''
   A shelter was set up for evacuees at Hart County High School, he
said.
</TEXT>
