<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Castro-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0608 12-04 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Castro-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0608,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Castro Says He Hopes Bush More Pragmatic Than Reagan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs with Castro calling U.S. Central American policy
a failure, criticizing South Africa</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Fidel Castro of Cuba said Saturday
that he hopes President-elect George Bush will be more pragmatic
than his predecessor in recognizing Latin American realities.
   ``It's always better to deal with a pragmatic man than to deal
with a man like President Reagan, who has a mind from the last
century, if that doesn't offend the last century,'' said Castro at a
news conference.
   But he said he he could not speculate on any changes in the
abrasive relationship between the United States and communist Cuba
under the new Bush administration.
   ``They say Bush is more pragmatic and less ideological than
Reagan,'' said Castro. ``But we'll have to see what happens and how
the new administration behaves.''
   Castro said his visit here for the inauguration of Carlos Salinas
de Gortari as president of Mexico is a sign that the United States'
long-term policy of isolating Cuba has fallen apart.
   ``Thirty years have gone by, and we're still here,'' he said.
Castro's forces overthrew the dictatorship of Fulgencio Batista on
Jan. 1, 1959. Castro noted that most countries in Latin America had
joined attempts to isolate Cuba.
   ``We never came to an inauguration before because they didn't
invite us,'' said Castro. ``But now Ecuador and Mexico have invited
us. U.S. policy is a total wreck, and Cuba's position is being
vindicated by Latin America.''
   He said he had met with Colombian president Virgilio Barco during
the Salinas festivities because ``although we don't have diplomatic
relations, we do have real relations.''
   ``We have never changed,'' he declared. ``But now, the situation
has changed.''
   He said he hopes the incoming Bush administration accepts the
reality of Latin America's staggering foreign debt problems and that
any agreement on the debt is the result of negotiation.
   ``It's not a small problem, like Grenada,'' said Castro. ``They
won't be able to resolve the problems created by the debt with the
82nd Airborne.''
   He said the Reagan administration's Central American policy had
failed in Nicaragua, El Salavador and Panama.
   ``One of the first tests of the Bush administration's pragmatic
spirit will be whether they are ready to negotiate with Nicaragua,''
he said.
   ``As far as Salvador is concerned, the test will be whether they
want to look for a solution by military means or by political
means.''
   Also during the three-hour news conference, Castro lashed out at
the South Africans, saying they ``aren't serious'' about peace in
their region.
   Talks aimed at a pullout of Cuban troops from Angola and
independence for South African-ruled Namibia broke off Saturday
without an agreement.
   Castro said more negotiations are needed, adding, ``If we have to
stay there another ten years, we will.''
</TEXT>
