<1ST_LINE>r a BC-SpaceShuttle     12-04 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Space Shuttle,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Atlantis Continues Secret Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military flight of space shuttle
Atlantis continued today with its usual official silence as the
public heard no word about the spaceship or its five crewmen.
   The silence results from a Defense Department policy to reveal as
little as possible about military shuttle missions.
   But no news was good news, for NASA and the Air Force said they
would break the silence only if a major problem developed.
   There was no information on whether the crew accomplished its
main goal: deploying a powerful all-weather radar satellite designed
to gather extremely sharp images of Eastern Bloc military
facilities. It would help American intelligence officials monitor
Soviet compliance with arms treaties.
   The satellite eventually will serve as the ``radar eye'' for the
new B-2 stealth bomber, picking out potential targets. That will
eliminate the need for the aircraft to use its own radar, which
might disclose its location.
   The astronauts were to release the satellite, with the code name
Lacrosse, on Saturday, reliable sources reported before the flight.
   The sources also said the astronauts were to conduct several
experiments aimed at defining man's role as a military observer in
space, with reconnaissance a high priority. It was believed they
would test a special optical device that resembles binoculars.
   The crew members are Navy Cmdr. Robert L. Gibson, the commander;
Air Force Lt. Col. Guy S. Gardner, the pilot; Col. Richard M.
Mullane and Lt. Col. Jerry L. Ross of the Air Force, and Navy Cmdr.
William M. Shepherd.
   The flight, which began Friday with a blazing liftoff from Cape
Canaveral, is expected to end Monday or Tuesday, with a landing at
Edwards Air Force Base, Calif.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration planned to
announce the landing time 24 hours in advance.
</TEXT>
