<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-88 1223EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Argentina     12-04 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Argentina,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civilian Evacuations Ordered As New Units Reported In Rebellion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today ordered
civilians evacuated from a neighborhood surrounding a rebel
stronghold in this capital as new military units were reported to
have joined the insurrection.
   Troop and tank movement was reported in several areas near Buenos
Aires as army loyalists apparently prepared to obey President Raul
Alfonsin's order to suppress the three-day revolt. Backup troops
also were reported being flown in from Neuquen, 750 miles southwest.
   It is the third army uprising since April 1987 and the latest
challenge to the civilian government since it restored democracy in
1983 after a nearly eight-year military dictatorship in which at
least 9,000 suspected leftists vanished without a trace.
   Mayor Carlos Brown of suburban San Martin was quoted by local
news agencies as saying he had received orders to evacuate all
civilians from the area surrounding a unit taken over Saturday by
about 500 rebels headed by Col. Mohamed Ali Seineldin.
   Police, firemen and civil defense volunteers began evacuating the
working-class residential area this morning.
   Reporters outside the 10th Logistical Batallion told local news
agenices the rebels appeared to fortifying their defense and had
moved a tank into position blocking the entrance.
   Alfonsin, as armed forces commander, sent a message to all
military units early today asking them to ``be alert to violent
options of some groups that march against history and hide their
real goals.''
   Although the majority of units throughout the country maintained
their loyalty, the official news agency Telam reported the 6th
Infantry Regiment in Mercedes, 62 miles west of the capital, had
joined the revolt led by Seineldin.
   The independent news agency Noticias Argentinas reported the 4th
Paratroop Brigade near Cordoba, 470 miles northwest, also joined the
insurrection.
   The government and political leaders called on Argentines to
demonstrate in town plazas across the country in favor of democracy
and in repudiation of the rebels. More than 100,000 were reported to
have filled plazas in Buenos Aires and Rosario, some staying
overnight.
   Sporadic shootings were reported overnight at Campo de Mayo, the
nation's largest army base on the outskirts of Buenos Aires where
Seineldin first took over an infantry school early Friday. There
were no reports of injuries.
   Four soldiers have been injured since the uprising began. Three
soldiers were wounded by a mine blast in January during a similar
army rebel uprising in Monte Caseros, 520 miles northeast of Buenos
Aires.
   Although surrounded, outgunned and outmanned by loyal troops, the
rebels were able to board trucks Saturday afternoon and drive
unhindered to the unit in the Villa Martelli neighborhood of San
Martin.
   Several explosions were heard Saturday night inside the
rebel-held unit, where angry civilians shouted insults and threw
rocks at troops wearing combat gear and camouflage paint.
   A bomb, tossed from a moving car, exploded but caused no damage
or injuries outside the 5th Infantry Brigade in northern Tucuman,
Telam reported.
   Alfonsin, who spent the night in the heavily guarded Government
House in downtown Buenos Aires, said Saturday night in a nationwide
radio and television address that he had ordered the army to
``suffocate'' the revolt.
   The army chief of staff, Gen. Jose Dante Caridi, simultaneously
issued a communique accusing Seineldin of trying to impose
``inadmisable conditions'' that endanger the constitution.
   The rebels, the army said, want ``changes in the government and
national authorities, the removal of the army chief of staff and his
replacement by a general picked by them,'' as well as the right to
select other high-ranking officers.
   The rebels earlier had also demanded an end to prosecution of
officers for human rights abuses committed during the dictatorship
and had sought an increase in the army's budget, trimmed as part of
the austerity measures taken by a government battling an annual
inflation rate of 330 percent.
</TEXT>
