<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-04 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brite & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska's biggest city is host to a moose
convention, only the conventioneers aren't the type who wear red
fezzes and nametags.
   Anchorage this fall is brimming with moose _ the animal type _
perhaps 900 of them, or 100 more than the total that feasted on
urban shrubbery two years ago, said the state Department of Fish and
Game.
   Moose are striding over cars, moseying around back yards and
chewing up mountain ash trees. The animals are bulling their way
through traffic, nosing around fast-food franchises and hanging
around a synagogue.
   ``We got a pot full o' moose around here,'' said state game
biologist Mike McDonald.
   The problem could get worse in the next two months, when moose
from the Chugach foothills make their move into the city to escape
the snow build-up at higher elevations, McDonald said.
   McDonald said the moose population has been helped by mild
winters the past two years. ``They pumped out calves like I can't
believe,'' McDonald said.
   Earlier this week, police said they watched a big bull moose
stroll across a parking lot and begin to step gingerly over a new
Pontiac. The moose dropped a hind foot and dented the hood.
   Then there's the cow and calf who live in a park across the
street from Temple Beth Sholom. Rabbi Harry Rosenfeld said they
visit nearly every night to munch on the synagogue's fruit trees or
peer through windows at services.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are cracking down on railroad
engineers who can't keep it down at night.
   Officers have begun ticketing engineers who blast their horns as
they travel through downtown in violation of a city noise ordinance.
   Officials of the Chicago & North Western and the Cedar Rapids and
Iowa City railroads, whose engineers were ticketed last week, said
horns must be sounded at crossings, despite the hour, to warn
pedestrians and motorists.
   City officials want railroads to use discretion between 10 p.m.
and 7 a.m. if no pedestrians or vehicles are nearby.
   After negotiations broke down last week, police were ordered to
ticket engineers who were deemed to have sounded horns
unnecessarily. ``Maybe we can do a little more negotiations now,''
Streets Commissioner Wayne Murdock said Friday.
   Murdock said the issue is a sore point at the Stouffer's Five
Seasons Hotel, where guests frequently are jolted from sleep in the
wee hours.
   ``I've seen ads from another hotel saying `Stay here, where you
don't have to worry about the trains,''' Murdock said.
</TEXT>
