<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-88 1122EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Collapse-Judge     12-04 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Collapse-Judge,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Who Settled Landmark Case Known for Gentle Persuasion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A handshake and promises were all that
sealed the more than $41 million settlement between 44 victims, 92
attorneys and over 40 companies in the L'Ambiance Plaza building
collapse before it was filed in court.
   That may have indicated the confidence the parties had in the
case's chief mediator, U.S. District Judge Robert C. Zampano.
   ``Obviously this (settlement) is the closest thing to the eighth
wonder of the world in the court's point of view,'' said U.S.
District Judge T.F. Gilroy Daly. ``All of us refer cases to him
(Zampano). He has extraordinary patience.''
   The settlement, signed Thursday, stemmed from the April 23, 1987,
collapse of a partially completed apartment complex in Bridgeport.
Twenty-eight men were killed and 16 injured.
   Claimants blamed the accident on lift-slab construction, in which
pre-cast concrete floors are hoisted into place.
   Zampano said there could have been hundreds of lawsuits and
thousands of counterclaims from the tragedy, and experts said it
could have taken 10 to 15 years for the lawsuits to go through the
court system.
   The mediation involved federal, state and probate courts, the
federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration and the state
Workers' Compensation Commission.
   ``We just took it one day at a time,'' Zampano said in an
interview Friday.
   Daly said Zampano is known for settling difficult cases out of
court and has a gift for listening in a ``kindly'' manner and
hearing what both sides really say.
   ``Everyone knows if Zampano takes a look at it ... if he can't do
it (mediate a settlement), I don't know who can,'' Daly said.
   Zampano, 59, is a graduate of Yale Law School and a former U.S.
attorney who began practicing law in 1954. He has been on the bench
for nearly 25 years.
   The L'Ambiance case was his most complex, he said. The months of
negotiations sometimes occurred on weekends, holidays and at night.
Zampano also handled his own cases during that time.
   He said he felt a twing of fear two days before Thanksgiving when
he realized no one had signed anything.
   ``It was all done by handshake. I thought what if someone said,
`I didn't promise you $3 million, I said $300,000,''' Zampano said.
``But nobody did.''
   In June, he and the other member of the mediation panel, Superior
Court Judge Frank S. Meadow, interviewed the victims' families. He
said it was the saddest month of his life. The case was like going
to 28 wakes and 28 funerals, he said.
   ``You just can't meet parties who suffered such great losses
without it being heart-wrenching,'' he said.
   Four months ago, an appraiser told him that the land on which the
building collapsed wasn't worth as much as it should be because of
the stigma. Under the settlement, the building will be
reconstructed, with some profits going to the victims.
   ``That has turned right around,'' Zampano said. ``Developers are
calling me and saying they want to be a part of it. Four months ago,
it was a monument to death, now it's a monument to life.''
   On Thursday, more than 200 people crowded into Zampano's
courtroom to watch the filing of the settlement.
   ``It took a person with his exceptional skills to accomplish
this,'' said U.S. Attorney Stanley A. Twardy Jr. ``A lot of judges
refer cases to him. He brings the parties together and works them
back and forth.''
   ``We negotiate every day in life, when buying a car or a house,''
Zampano said. ``But for some reason when people get in a lawsuit the
general feeling is we'll fight to the finish.
   ``But when we bring them in, they really don't want to go to
court. If you can bring both sides in, sit down and rationally talk
it out, more than 95 percent of the cases should be settled.''
</TEXT>
