<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MissingOrwell     12-04 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Orwell,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Lost' George Orwell Play Turns Up 56 Years Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old boy who tucked away the script of a
school play written by his teacher unwittingly preserved the only
known copy of a drama by author George Orwell, the Sunday Times
reported.
   The short historical drama, entitled ``King Charles II,'' about
the king's flight to France after his father's execution will be
auctioned by Sotheby's in London on Dec. 15, the weekly said.
   Orwell wrote the play while teaching at the private Hawthorns
high school in Hayes outside London in 1932, the year before he
changed his name from Eric Blair with the publication of his first
book, ``Down and Out in Paris and London.''
   Geoffrey Stevens, a retired construction merchant, told the
newspaper it was not until many years later that he realized his
teacher at Hawthorns was the famous author of ``Animal Farm'' and
``1984'' and that he had pocketed a literary treasure.
   ``He was Mr. Blair and that was how we knew him,'' Stevens was
quoted as saying. ``Of course, I had heard of George Orwell much
later. I just never realized they were one and the same until I was
reading an article about him and saw his photograph.
   ``I always thought there was something special about him _ a
lofty teacher who seemed in a world of his own,'' he was quoted as
saying. ``I don't know why I preserved his play. I suppose I liked
him enormously and I keep most things. I'm glad I did.''
   The school play idea was used in Orwell's second novel, ``A
Clergyman's Daughter,'' the newspaper said.
   Stevens is selling the typescript acting copy, on which his first
name is written twice in red crayon, it said.
   According to the auction house catalog, Sotheby's estimates the
play will fetch between $2,775 and $3,700.
</TEXT>
