<DOCNO> AP881204-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-88 1124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Girls'Strike     12-04 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Girls' Strike,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girls Strike To Go To School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of girls has gone on strike in a village
in south China, refusing to do housework, tend the fields or take
care of their siblings unless their parents let them attend school,
according to a report seen Sunday.
   ``We want to go to school and study,'' one of the 14 girls was
quoted as saying. ``And if our families won't let us, we'll make
trouble. If we don't win this one, our lives will be finished.'' Her
name was not provided.
   The Communist Party newspaper the Peasant Daily said the girls,
between 8 and 15 years old, are fighting an antiquated Chinese
tradition which holds that education is for men only.
   But they are also battling recent economic changes that have made
education more costly for many peasant families.
   ``Most of the girls from Jia Cui village aren't allowed to go to
school,'' said the report about the village in Guangxi province.
``Those few that do go only make it to the third or fourth grade.''
   China's education system faces a shortage of funds as the cost of
books, electricity, food and other services has soared due to rising
inflation.
   As a result, many schools have started levying fees,
contradicting an official policy of free education for all.
   In the cities, teams of workers often pay these fees, but in the
countryside individual households are often stuck with the bill. So
peasant families tend to send their boys to school and keep their
girls at home.
   In this way, China's new economic difficulties are reinforcing
old sexual distinctions that kept women uneducated and bound to the
home.
   Indeed, an official study released earlier this year said that
women make up 64 percent of the illiterates in China.
   In addition, it said that girls comprise 83 percent of the
country's 2.7 million school-aged children who have not yet started
school.
   The newspaper report, published Saturday, said many meetings have
been held in the village to persuade families to let their children
go to school.
   ``Last semester, a teacher even started night classes for
girls,'' the paper said, ``but night classes need lamp oil and no
families would give any. The classes lasted one month and then
folded.''
   The paper quoted the mother of one of the strikers as saying she
opposed her daughter's action.
   ``Girls have got to marry early. If they don't stay at home and
learn to do labor and craft work now, they won't marry well later
on,'' the mother said.
   So far, eight of the girls have been allowed to go to school. The
others are waiting for the village to set up another night class,
the paper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
