<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Australia-Yugoslavia     12-04 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Australia-Yugoslavia,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Staff Of Yugoslav Consulate Leaves Australia Under Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Complying with an order from the
Australian government, Yugoslavia closed its consulate Sunday and
called its staff home, including a security guard accused of
shooting a demonstrator.
   The departure of 12-member staff and their families ended a
standoff between the two nations that began last week when the guard
allegedly shot and wounded a teen-ager during a Croatian
demonstration outside the consulate.
   Australia ordered the consulate closed after it refused to allow
Australian authorities to question the guard.
   Yugoslavia protested the order expelling the diplomats and
claimed that the guard fired in self-defense when demonstrators
charged the consulate and Australian authorities were unable to stop
them.
   Security was tight Sunday when police escorted cars carrying the
Yugoslavs from the consulate in the Sydney suburb of Woollahra to
the airport, where they departed on a Yugoslav Airlines flight
Sunday night.
   More than 100 police guarded the airport, but an expected
demonstration by Croatians failed to occur.
   The Australian government has reserved the right to claim
compensation from Yugoslav officials for the family of Jospeh Tokic,
16, who was shot in the throat during the protest on Nov. 27,
Yugoslav National Day.
   Yugoslav authorities said the guard, identified as Matijas Zoran,
fired in self-defense when several Croatian youths began scaling the
consulate walls. Croatians are among several ethnic groups in
Yugoslavia.
   About 200,000 Yugoslavs live in Australia.
   Yugoslavia strongly criticized Australia on Saturday for closing
the consulate and expelling its staff, but did not did not threaten
to retaliate.
</TEXT>
