<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HouseLeadership     12-04 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House Leadership,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Time Of Change, The House Is Bastion of Stability</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a year in which the White House will have a
new occupant and the Senate will be under new leadership, the House
of Representatives promises to be a bastion of stability.
   House Democrats and Republicans meet this week to elect their
leaders and appear likely to return most of the top positions to the
same hands, including House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas and Minority
Leader Robert Michel of Illinois.
   Wright's ethics problems _ he is being investigated for alleged
financial improprieties and on charges he improperly disclosed
classified information _ have stirred some unease among Democrats,
but do not appear to have threatened his leadership position.
   Other top Democrats in the group that took power in 1987 will
also retain their posts: Thomas Foley of Washington as majority
leader, Tony Coelho of California as majority whip and David Bonior
of Michigan as Coelho's chief deputy.
   ``There's no question, the team is together,'' Coehlo said. ``It
worked together for two years... I think that we had an excellent
two years, very, very productive.
   ``You had a speaker who set an agenda,'' in marked contrast to
that of President Reagan and managed to wrest control over much of
U.S. policy, Coehlo said.
   The only real battle on the Democratic side, when the votes are
cast Monday behind the closed doors of the House chamber, will be
for the chairmanship of the House Democratic Caucus, the policy
organization of all House Democrats. The position holds no real
powers, but it can be used as a platform for gaining visibility, as
it did for its previous occupant, Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.
   Rep. William Gray, D-Pa., is seen by many as the favorite to win
the post after campaigning hard all year and spending more than
$115,000 on campaign contributions to fellow Democrats, including 99
members of the 101st Congress.
   His chief opponent, Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, has charged
that Gray's effort has improperly injected big money into an
internal House race for the first time. Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla.,
also is seeking the post.
   Either Gray or Oakar, now the vice chairman of the caucus, would
be trailblazers for the Democrats.
   Gray would be the first black to gain a rung on the House
administrative leadership ladder that can lead to the speaker's job.
He is completing the maximum four years as Budget Committee
chairman. A win for Oakar would make her the first woman to break
into the party's top leadership.
   Michel is unopposed for minority leader, the top Republican
leadership position he has held for the past eight years.
   There will be a shift in the No. 2 slot for the GOP, as
Republican Conference chairman Dick Cheney of Wyoming moves up to be
minority whip, a post vacated by Mississippi's Trent Lott as he
moves over to the Senate.
   The only fight on the Republican side is over who will succeed
Cheney as conference chairman.
   Normally, the heir apparent would be Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif.,
who has been the party's policy committee chairman. But he faces a
stiff challenge from Rep. Lynn Martin of Illinois, a quick,
outspoken lawmaker who has been conference vice chairman. Also
running for the post is Rep. William Dannemeyer, R-Calif.
   The House meetings come a week after the Senate informally
convened to get organized for the coming year and Democrats elected
Sen. George Mitchell of Maine to succeed West Virginia's Robert Byrd
as majority leader.
   In their meetings, House Democrats also will consider a list of
proposed rules changes, including one proposed by Rep. Charles
Stenholm, D-Texas, to force disclosure of who would benefit from
special-interest provisions in legislation.
   The proposal would require the listing of the name of each
beneficiary, the cost to taxpayers of the provision, and the name of
the lawmaker who sponsored it. The aim is to prevent members of
Congress who vote for a bill from later being embarrassed by
discovery of special-interest provisions.
   Stenholm's suggestion was considered by a leadership panel, which
declined to support it on grounds that it would impose unreasonable
burdens on committees, particularly the tax and spending panels
which most frequently deal with special-interest measures.
</TEXT>
