<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LeeThomas Bjt   12-04 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lee Thomas, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Departing Environmental Bureaucrat's Reflections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Thomas says he was proud to be leading the
``tree-huggers'' _ the nickname for people who put environmental
concerns above all else _ out of the closet at the Environmental
Protection Agency.
   Concern for natural resources _ swamps, endangered species, green
and furry things _ ``is not something to be looked down on,'' Thomas
said in an interview marking the close of his nearly four years as
administrator of the government's largest regulatory agency.
   It isn't widely recognized that the laws guiding EPA are heavily
aimed at protecting health. In the agency, ``We had lost the sense
we had both missions, and that one was connected to the other,''
Thomas said.
   ``If you don't protect wetlands, you're eventually going to have
major problems in water quality _ eventually that translates into
health issues.''
   To a remark that the agency sometimes seemed ``full of closet
tree-huggers,'' Thomas replied with emphasis, ``As it should be.''
It was clear Thomas was refusing to accept the term as one of
derision.
   Asked which accomplishments he is proud of, the first concrete
actions he lists are the little-noticed establishment of a Wetlands
Office in EPA and a program focusing protection of estuaries, the
wide mouths of rivers where the tide meets the fresh water.
   Ahead of those he lists an intangible achievement, the
establishment of U.S. leadership in international discussions of
global climate change.
   Thomas was not known as a tree-hugger of any variety when he came
to EPA.
   He has degrees in education and psychology and was a family-court
probation officer before becoming director of public safety in the
South Carolina governor's office, where his duties included
management of emergencies.
   He came to Washington in 1981 as associate director of the
Federal Emergency Management Agency. He directed flood relief
efforts in 1982 at the dioxin-contaminated town of Times Beach, Mo.,
later supervising the federal buyout of residents' homes.
   Success attracted White House attention. President Reagan
nominated him as assistant EPA administrator to oversee the
superfund toxic waste cleanup program, succeeding the fired Rita
Lavelle early in 1983.
   He was to have been part of a team of managers the White House
sent in to shape up an agency in turmoil over accusations of
political manipulation of superfund.
   Impressed with what he saw as rare administrative selflessness
and openness, EPA administrator William D. Ruckelshaus recommended
Thomas as his successor when he resigned in late 1984.
   Thomas has been there ever since in a job he calls ``the best job
in Washington ... and the worst,'' one that leaves the holder
``aware of the fact you're not going to get any `Attaboys!' from any
side.''
   Thomas is leaving without any idea what he will do next.
   His biggest disappointment, he said, was the failure of Congress
to decide what to do about the 68 cities and rural counties that
failed to meet federal air quality standards for ozone at the 1987
deadline.
   ``We're kind of in limbo,'' he said.
   The debate over the Clean Air Act, according to some in Congress,
illustrates what they say is Thomas' big shortcoming.
   ``He was cooperative, but we got no leadership out of the White
House when we absolutely needed it,'' said Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla.,
chairman of the environment and natural resources subcommittee of
the House Government Operations Committee.
   ``Lee Thomas is very sharp, well-respected, knowledgeable on the
issues, and no question about it, very bright. He has continued to
restore the credibility of the agency ... but he doesn't have
political clout down at the White House.''
   Peter A.A. Berle, president of the National Audubon Society,
makes a similar but more favorable assessment: ``He has struggled
mightily, in some areas successfully and in some areas not so
successfully. He has had practically no support from the White
House. ... I would have hoped he would have cut through some of the
bureaucracy around superfund.''
   In the agency, Thomas is considered a bureaucrat's bureaucrat,
and it's a bureaucrat's improvement he suggests _ for Congress.
   Congress, he said, ``ought to step back and look at their
organizational arrangements for dealing with EPA.'' With 75
committees and subcommittees, according to the agency's count,
claiming a piece of the action, ``they just don't have the structure
to do any kind of priority setting.''
   ``The interest groups say, `I want it done my way and the only
way I can make sure it's done my way is to have it written into the
law.''
   Even though Congress spells out details such as how many
superfund investigations must be completed by specific dates, Thomas
believes it sometimes shies away from what should be the major point.
   In the last session's clean air debates, Thomas said he never got
a clear answer from members to the question, ``Are you willing to
say a maximum individual risk (of cancer) of one in 10,000 is OK
because the alternative is to shut the plant down? That's a decision
I have to make.''
</TEXT>
