<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gorbachev-Traffic     12-04 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Traffic,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Motorists: Stay Away During Soviet Leader's Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists in New York are bracing for
``Gorbylock'' _ traffic jams of superpower proportions during
Mikhail Gorbachev's visit this week.
   ``But remember: It's gridlock for the sake of world peace,'' said
Samuel Schwartz, deputy transportation commissioner.
   The Soviet leader is scheduled to arrive Tuesday. He will meet
with President Reagan and Vice President George Bush on Governor's
Island on Wednesday, tour the city on Thursday and leave Friday.
   Among the possibilities are visits to the Metropolitan Museum of
Art, Times Square and Wall Street. Gorbachev will travel in a
heavily guarded, 40-car motorcade.
   ``If he goes through Times Square, we expect he might get out of
his car to shake hands,'' said Alice McGillion, a police
spokeswoman. ``It's a movable riot.''
   Wednesday and Thursday are expected to be the worst days for
traffic. In addition to the Christmas shopping rush, Wednesday is
matinee day on Broadway, which can add 50,000 vehicles to the
860,000 that normally enter Manhattan.
   ``Dec. 7 will be a day of infamy,'' Schwartz said.
   ``We're advising motorists to go public, take public
transportation. The easiest way to get around will be to walk.
Certain areas may have to be frozen as the Soviet leader moves
about.''
</TEXT>
