<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-88 1306EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MourningElephants     12-04 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mourning Elephants,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Herd Tries To Save Wounded Calf, Mourns When He Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For two days, a herd of elephants nursed
a wounded elephant calf after nudging him along the road to the
nearest human protection in the forests of eastern India, United
News of India reported Sunday.
   It took the elephants six hours to cover the two miles to their
destination, a forest rangers' office. The staff administered first
aid to the 2-year-old calf, but he later succumbed to head wounds
inflicted by a tiger.
   Tears rolled out of the mother elephant's eyes as the rest of the
herd formed a circle, raised their trunks and trumpeted over the
body.
   UNI said the tale was related by S.G. Ochi, project manager of
forest development in Simlipal National Park in Orissa state, 140
miles west of Calcutta.
   Ochi said the herd of about 25 elephants apparently was grazing
in a grasslands about two 2 miles from the rangers' office when a
tiger tried to seize the calf.
   Devandra Nayak, a tracker for Project Tiger, a government
organization trying to save tigers from extinction, watched the
herd's progress as it brought the calf to the rangers' office. Nayak
said the herd paused intermittently to let the wounded elephant rest.
   When the elephants reached a salt lick near the rangers' office,
the mother elephant picked up a clump of dry grass in her trunk and
fanned flies away from her calf's head wound.
   The elephants apparently thought the proximity of people would
keep the tiger from returning for the kill, UNI said.
   According to the report, as the midday sun shone down and the
heat grew intense, most of the herd sought shelter under some trees
300 feet away. The mother left her calf in search of water.
   The rangers took advantage of the herd's temporary absence to
wash the calf's wound and apply ointment.
   Then the mother returned, chasing the rangers. She sprayed water
on the calf to cool him and kept vigil, with the rest of the herd,
until he died the following day.
   The herd again disappeared, and the staff buried the calf.
   For the next two nights the herd returned and thumped the loose
earth covering the calf's body.
   UNI said the episode occurred recently, but it did not give a
date.
</TEXT>
