<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-88 1312EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Democrats-Blacks     12-04 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Blacks,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Looking to Avoid Racial Fight Over Party Chairmanship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Republican president-elect George Bush
was having a cordial lunch with Jesse Jackson recently, Democrats
were hoping that a contest for their party chairmanship wouldn't
become a racial fight.
   ``If we're not careful and we turn the chairmanship fight into a
racial thing then, yes, we can alienate everybody,'' said Jim
Ruvolo, chairman of the Ohio Democratic Party.
   That was a big reason why many Democrats were waiting anxiously
to hear on Monday whether Paul G. Kirk Jr. was willing to seek a
second, four-year term as chairman.
   Kirk, under heavy pressure from party leaders to stay in his job,
planned to announce his decision at a Monday afternoon news
conference.
   At a meeting last month with state Democratic Party leaders, Kirk
indicated his reluctance, saying, ``Four years is a long time and
eight years is twice as long.''
   But the party chairman has received appeals from party leaders,
including the defeated Democratic presidential ticket of Michael
Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen, to stay on.
   While Kirk has received near-unanimous praise for the job he has
done the past four years, another reason for the appeals was the
desire to avoid a fight to succeed him that could divide the party
along racial lines.
   Interested in competing for the chairmanship if Kirk does not run
are Ron Brown, a Washington lawyer who was convention manager for
Jackson; Rick Wiener of Michigan, president of the Association of
Democratic State Chairs; and former Reps. James Stanton of Ohio,
James Jones of Oklahoma and Michael Barnes of Maryland.
   Brown, a former party vice chairman, has openly chafed at the
fact that opposition to him is based on his role in the Jackson
campaign.
   ``I think Ron Brown is right when he says he's been around the
Democratic Party longer than Jesse Jackson,'' said Ruvolo, likely to
succeed Wiener as head of the state chairs association.
   All but Brown have said they would bow out of the contest if Kirk
decides to seek another term. Brown has refused to make such a
commitment although of the impact it would have on his plans he has
said if Kirk runs ``obviously it makes it more difficult, obviously
it's less likely.''
   The potential fight for the chairmanship was not the only
Democratic Party contest that could divide over racial lines during
the next year.
   In New York, Mayor Ed Koch, who is up for re-election in 1989,
outraged blacks and many whites during the 1988 presidential primary
campaign when he said supporters of Israel would ``have to be
crazy'' to vote for Jackson.
   Mayoral races in Chicago and Los Angeles also could produce
bitter contests between black and white candidates.
   While the Democrats were trying to avoid battles that could
alienate their most loyal constituency, the Republicans were taking
aim at attracting more black support.
   Bush met with Jackson and said he and the former Democratic
presidential aspirant have a ``relationship that transcends
politics.''
   ``There will be times ... when I will ask for his suggestions,''
Bush said of Jackson. ``He has some very good ideas.''
   In turn, Jackson praised Bush for his ``openness'' and his
willingness ``to discuss a broad range of matters.''
   Lee Atwater, Bush's campaign manager and the president-elect's
choice to become next Republican Party chairman, said he would make
a special effort in his new post to attract black voters to the GOP.
</TEXT>
