<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Switzerland-Vote     12-04 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Switzerland-Vote,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swiss Reject Amendment To Limit Number Of Foreigners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swiss voters on Sunday rejected by 2-1 a proposed
constitutional amendment that would have cut the nation's 1 million
foreign residents by almost one third in the next 15 years.
   A referendum proposal to introduce a 40-hour work week also was
decisively turned down.
   Official returns indicated that 67.3 percent of the voters
rejected the immigration measure. The 40-hour work week was turned
down by 65.8 percent of the voters.
   Officials estimated turnout at 50 percent.
   The immigration measure, launched by the small, right-wing
National Action Party, would have reduced the number of foreigners
among Switzerland's 6.5 million people from 1 million to about
700,000 by the year 2004.
   Supporters said this would be achieved by admitting only two new
immigrants for every three foreigners leaving Switzerland.
   The plan also called for sharply cutting the number of foreign
seasonal workers and of people working in Switzerland but living in
France, Italy, West Germany or Austria.
   The government this year reported a record influx of refugees,
many from Third World countries, seeking asylum in Switzerland. More
than 13,000 foreigners were expected to apply for asylum in
Switzerland this year, up about 30 percent from last year.
   National Action claimed the proposed measure would deter
thousands of people from seeking asylum, thus saving money, easing a
housing shortage and reducing environmental burdens.
   The labor proposal, launched by the Swiss Federation of Trade
Unions, called for annual two-hour reductions in the workweek until
all industries reached the 40-hour standard in 1999. The workweek
now averages 42.5 hours, but workers in catering, sales or hospitals
put in 43 to 60 hours.
   The government had urged citizens to reject both draft
amendments, warning of serious economic consequences in a country
already facing a tight labor market.
   Critics said the immigration measure would sap the work force in
the construction and catering industries, forcing businesses to shut
down or move abroad. They also warned of strained relations with the
12-nation European Economic Community, Switzerland's largest trading
partner.
   Employers and the government argued that the proposed labor
legislation would reduce the flexibility of unions and industries to
negotiate the length of the work week. Several industries, including
watchmaking and machinery, have adopted the 40-hour standard or have
pledged to introduce it.
   In Switzerland, more than 100,000 signatures were required to put
the two referendum issues on the ballot.
</TEXT>
