<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EEC-Thatcher     12-04 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EEC-Thatcher,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anglo-Irish Showdown Over Priest Shatters European Summit Harmony</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RHODES, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A showdown between British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher and Belgian and Irish leaders over extradition of
a pro-IRA priest marred a European Economic Community summit and
plunged Anglo-Irish relations to a new low.
   The EEC meeting, which ended Saturday, also displayed strains
over the next big hurdles the 12-nation trade bloc faces _ such a
single tax system and free migration _ as it becomes a huge, single
market by 1992.
   But it was the issue of Patrick Ryan, a Roman Catholic priest who
British authorities charge is linked with a string of Irish
Republican Army bombings, that exploded into some of the angriest
exchanges yet between the fellow West European leaders.
   As with the other big diversion in Rhodes, the presence of Greek
Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou's blonde girlfriend, Dimitra
Liani, the other heads of government pretended not to notice.
   It wasn't easy.
   Mrs. Thatcher devoted much of a news conference at the end of the
summit Saturday to renewed expressions of outrage against Belgian
Prime Minister Wilfried Martens, whose government refused to
extradite Ryan, and Charles Haughey, premier of the Irish Republic,
where the priest is holed up with an undisclosed religious order.
   ``It is not enough to sign ringing declarations against
terrorism. What matters is effective action,'' she snapped. ``We are
at the receiving end of vicious terrorist attacks. It our police, it
is our soldiers, our civilians ... who are being maimed or killed.''
   Nearly 3,000 people have died in Protestant-Catholic feuding in
British-ruled Northern Ireland in the past 20 years.
   Mrs. Thatcher herself narrowly escaped injury or death in 1984
when the IRA blew up her hotel in Brighton, England, and killed five
people.
   The mainly Catholic guerrilla movement, banned in both Britain
and Ireland, remains pledged to try to kill her in its drive to
unite Northern Ireland with the Irish Republic.
   Haughey and Martens, berated in separate meetings by Mrs.
Thatcher, refused to back down, denying political motivations and
saying they acted on purely legal grounds.
   Belgium, where Ryan was arrested in June, sent him to Ireland
last week after the 58-year-old priest went on hunger strike in jail.
   Mrs. Thatcher's anger at the Belgian action turned to fury as
Irish police let Ryan disappear while the Irish Attorney General
John Murray ponders the extradition request.
   ``It would be foolish to deny that this is an event of major
signifigance in Anglo-Irish relations that has caused major fallout
in many different directions,'' Haughey told Irish journalists at
the end of a tough session with Mrs. Thatcher on Saturday.
   On Friday, citing ``personal convenience,'' Haughey canceled a
scheduled meeting with Mrs. Thatcher at the hotel where they were
both staying.
   Not even Mrs. Thatcher said it publicly: but behind the Ryan
dispute lies an insinuation by Britain, a mainly Protestant nation,
that Belgium and Ireland, overwhelmingly Catholic countries, are
being faint-hearted because Ryan is a priest.
   The confrontation has thrown new strains on a 1985 accord which
gave the republic a consultative say in the running of Northern
Ireland.
   To many Irish, the confrontation smacks of another example of
British heavy-handedness, exacerbated by what some see as Mrs.
Thatcher pursuit of a personal war against the IRA regardless of
diplomatic or democratic niceties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
