<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Arafat     12-04 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arafat,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Says He'll Wait and See What Bush Policy Will Be</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat said Sunday he would
``wait and see'' if a U.S. refusal to grant him an entry visa was an
indication of things to come under the new Bush adminstration.
   Arafat made the comments after meeting with President Hosni
Mubarak to discuss the Palestinian leader's planned speech to the
U.N. General Assembly in Geneva.
   The assembly is to convene in Geneva Dec. 13-15. The session was
arranged after the State Department denied Arafat a visa to address
the world body during an annual debate on Palestine.
   The U.S. move provoked worldwide criticism.
   Asked if the decision was a reflection of future U.S. policy
under President-elect George Bush, Arafat was quoted as saying: ``I
prefer to wait and see. This is better.''
   Arafat and Mubarak said they still were exerting efforts to bring
peace to the Middle East.
   ``We all want peace and we all want a solution for the
(Palestinian) issue and we are all far away from terrorism and we
all hope that the Middle East will become stable and that everyone
will live in security, including Israel,'' Mubarak told reporters
after the talks.
   The official Middle East News Agency reported the comments of
both leaders.
   Arafat arrived Saturday night, his second visit to Cairo in 10
days. Because of security measures, his schedule is never published
in advance and it was not clear how long his stay would be.
   He has been touring Arab states since the Palestine Liberation
Organization's parliament-in-exile, the Palestine National Council,
proclaimed an independent state last month and implicitly recognized
Israel. Those moves will be the main focus of Arafat's address to
the General Assembly.
   ``I hope (Arafat's) speech will be successful and that it will
convince the international world opinion more and more of the
Palestinian issue which we consider the main cause for instability
in the region,'' Mubarak was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
