<HEAD>American Missionary Protests Confiscation Of Bible Booklets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of an American missionary agency said
Sunday that Chinese customs officials had confiscated thousands of
Bible booklets he had planned to distribute in communist China.
   Rev. Eddie Karnes, general director of World Harvesters, Inc.,
said the Bible booklets were seized Saturday when he and an American
friend tried to enter China from Hong Kong as tourists.
   Karnes said the officials threw the 2,500 leaflets into burlap
bags, but later returned them when he decided not to enter China.
   He said he had planned to go to the southern Chinese city of
Canton, where he had distributed Bible booklets last week.
   Karnes said he has sent a telegram to President Reagan and
President-elect George Bush protesting what he called ``Chinese
religious apartheid.'' The missionary said he would call for
Christians worldwide to boycott Chinese goods.
   World Harvesters, Inc. is a missionary agency based in Yelm, Wash.
