<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     12-04 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oppositon Demands Parliament Dissolve Before Presidential Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders Sunday demanded the
dissolution of Parliament before a new president is chosen, claiming
the present government is incapable of running a fair election.
   President Junius R. Jayewardene on Saturday announced Parliament
would be dissolved one day after the presidential election on Dec.
19. He also called parliamentary elections for Feb. 15.
   The opposition, however, said the parliamentary elections will
come too late to stop state assistance to the governing United
National Freedom Party.
   ``Our main demand has been Parliament be dissolved before ... the
presidential poll on Dec. 19, because all government machinery is
being used by Prime Minister Ranasinghe Premadasa to continue his
campaign for the presidency,'' said Kumar Ponnambalam, general
secretary of the Ceylon Tamil Congress and spokesman for the
oppostion Democratic People's Alliance.
   Ponnambalam's alliance includes the largest opposition group, the
Sri Lanka Freedom Party.
   The strongest challenge to the United National Party comes from
the leader of the Freedom Party, former Prime Minister Sirimavo
Bandaranaike.
   But Buddhist and Christian leaders praised President Junius R.
Jayewardene's decision to call new parliamentary elections.
   ``We welcome the decision by President Jayewardene to dissolve
Parliament ... and advance general elections to mid-February from
the scheduled end-of-August time frame,'' said Venerable Palipanne
Chandananda, a Buddhist clergyman whose post is the equivalent of a
Christian archbishop.
   The Buddhist clergy have been a powerful political force in Sri
Lanka, where most of the Sinhalese ethnic majority are Buddhist.
   Chandananda, contacted by telephone in Kandy, 55 miles east of
Colombo, said the decision to conduct elections in February was ``a
positive response by the head of state.''
   Archbishop Marcus Fernando, head of the Roman Catholic clergy,
also welcomed the early election.
   ``It is a positive response to a public demand,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
   Christians are a minority in Sri Lanka, drawing followers from
the Tamils, the Sinhalese and the Burghers, who are descended from
European colonists.
   Sri Lanka has been wracked by five years of ethnic bloodshed in
which minority Tamils are fighting the Sinhalese for an independent
homeland in the northeast. More than 9,000 people have been killed
since 1983 in massacres, bombings, assassinations and guerrilla
warfare.
   Sinhalese radicals have criticized the Sinhalese-dominated
government for its efforts to make peace with the Tamils.
   Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
while Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, represent 18 percent.
</TEXT>
