<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Priscilla Presley exposes a little-seen funny
bone in the slapstick film ``The Naked Gun.''
   Coming from the glitz and drama of oil-rich high society in
television's ``Dallas,'' the one-time wife of Elvis Presley shifted
gears to play comic foil to Leslie Nielsen and Ricardo Montalban in
her movie debut.
   ``They had me doing things I never did before,'' she said. ``They
had me laughing at myself. I was making fun of myself. I was making
fun of glamour. I was making fun of being attractive. It's what I
needed to do.''
   ``At first I'd think `This can't be funny,''' she said. ``And
then we would do a scene and we would hear the crew dying of
laughter, and then we knew we had it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union
has honored Kirk Douglas for openly hiring blacklisted screenwriter
Dalton Trumbo to write his 1960 film ``Spartacus.''
   Douglas received the ACLU's annual Bill of Rights Award at a
dinner Saturday celebrating the 197th birthday of the Bill of Rights.
   Trumbo was among many Hollywood figures blacklisted during the
anti-Communist backlash of the 1950s. Douglas, who co-produced
``Spartacus,'' is credited with the first public hiring of a someone
blacklisted for alleged Communist sympathies.
   Trumbo served 10 months in prison for contempt of Congress for
refusing to testify before the House Un-American Activities
Committee. He later won an Oscar for his script for ``The Brave
One,'' written under the name Robert Rich.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TONKA BAY, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Mrs. America's schedule has
included a meeting with the president and dozens of parades and
interviews, but Jennifer Kline is used to moving fast.
   Mrs. Kline, 22, who was crowned Oct. 30 in Kauai, Hawaii, skipped
third grade in St. Cloud, Minn., and was one of the youngest in her
high school class of 1983.
   After being spotted in a 1983 amateur fashion contest in St.
Cloud, she quickly became one of the Twin Cities' top models. She
met her husband, Rick Kline, on Valentine's Day in 1986 and married
him just seven months later.
   And as a late entrant to the Mrs. Minnesota contest, Kline said
she had to train swiftly to win the state and national crowns.
   ``I am so anxious to get out there and talk to married women,''
she said. ``People have connotations of married women being
has-beens. This (pageant) shows that married women can do what
single women do.''
