<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-88 1537EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Festival     12-04 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Festival,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Musicians Participate in Buddhist Festival</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minimalist composer Philip Glass, Grateful Dead
percussionist Mickey Hart and Japanese synthesizer player Kitaro
took part in a Tibetan Ganden Ngam Cho, or ``festival of light,''
Saturday night at the Cathedral Church of St. John the Divine.
   It was the first time Western musicians participated in the music
performed on this Tibetan Buddhist holiday.
   By coincidence, it also was the first night of Hanukkah, the
Jewish ``festival of lights.''
   Twenty Gyuto monks, the Gyuto Tantric Choir, sat in two lines on
the floor of a stage and sang nine chants. The music sounded more
like a gutteral drone than a chant, with each note and syllable held
a long time, and most of it was lower than the deepest bass at a
Western opera house.
   While some voices hit a low note and held it, others hit tones
just above or below the main note. This gave a fullness and
resonance, but the tones were so close together it didn't sound like
harmony.
   When higher tones were held, it sounded like a large choir
singing a unison ``amen'.
   Actor Richard Gere, president of Tibet House here and master of
ceremonies, said that proceeds from a TV film and recording made at
the event will help build a Gyuto Buddhist monastery in Nepal. There
now is one monastery, in India. It was built after China invaded
Tibet in 1950, and a few of the 900 Gyuto Buddhist monks fled to
India.
   Saturday was the 25th day of the 10th lunar month, the date of
both the birth and death of Tsong Khapa. Robert Thurman, a professor
at Columbia University, said that Tsong Khapa revitalized Buddhism
in Tibet and started a Gyuto monastery 514 years ago.
   He said that the music offered on this festival makes a listener
momentarily free of ``stinginess, egotism, anger, poverty, pain and
fear'' and able to feel ``love, clarity and joy.''
   Once, public performances of chants by monks were not considered
appropriate.
   Glass, playing organ at the back of the church, Kitaro playing
synthesizer, and Hart, with two percussion instruments, in front of
the stage where the monks sat, played a 20-minute piece of modified
minimalist music before the monks chanted. Miles Davis, who was
scheduled to play, was ill and was replaced by Kitaro.
   Thurman said the guests were invited to play because the monks
feel that ``from their hearts, musicians come out and play and
celebrate truth. The monks envision them as dieties making offerings
to the Buddha.''
   Hart's 360 Productions and Tibet House are sponsoring the monks'
U.S. visit, which began in early November on the West Coast and
continues to Philadelphia, Boston and Northampton, Mass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
