<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TexasPower     12-04 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Power,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texans Coming Home To Roost In Nation's Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas power is on the upswing in Washington,
where Lone Star State clout just may eclipse those potent days when
Sam Rayburn was speaker of the House and Lyndon B. Johnson headed
the Senate.
   ``Things are looking good for us,'' says Rep. Jack Brooks,
D-Texas. ``You've got Democrats taking over Congress and Republicans
taking over the administration from Texas.''
   Adopted Texan George Bush assumes the presidency on Jan. 20,
bringing with him at least two and as many as five Cabinet members
from Texas. House Speaker Jim Wright, who hails from Fort Worth, is
likely to retain his leadership post in voting this week.
   James A. Baker III, Bush's nominee for secretary of State, is
from Houston while Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos, the first
Hispanic member of a president's Cabinet, is the son of a cowhand
and former president of Texas Tech University.
   The Texas list goes on in Congress where Rep. Kika de la Garza is
chairman of the Agriculture Committee and Reps. Brooks and Henry B.
Gonzalez are in line to take over the House Judiciary and Banking
committees, respectively.
   On the Republican side, former Texas Sen. John Tower is under
serious consideration for secretary of Defense, Houston businessman
Robert Mosbacher is rumored a contender for secretary of Commerce
and former congressman Tom Loeffer is mentioned for secretary of
Energy.
   ``This is the first time in our history that we've had a Texan as
president and as speaker of the House. And we have a number of
Texans as chairmen of committees now,'' says Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
himself the chairman of the Senate Finance Committee.
   ``I've never seen that many Texans holding that many positions.
We'll certainly get some attention to our (state's) concerns,'' said
the defeated Democratic vice presidential nominee.
   ``When you're in power you're in style, and Texas is back in
style,'' says Democratic consultant George Shipley of Austin.
   Bush would break the record for Texans in the Cabinet if he
appoints at least four, according to George Christian, who served as
press secretary to Johnson from 1966 to 1969. The most Texans at any
one time in Johnson's Cabinet was three, Christian says.
   ``Historically, Texans have had strong leadership in Washington,
but the difference is today it has a bipartisan tinge to it that it
didn't have before,'' says Christian. ``We have feet in both camps,
and that's an improvement.''
   ``It's really a Texas brigade in the North,'' says Bob Mansker,
press secretary to Democratic Rep. Martin Frost of Dallas.
   It's a heady ascent for the state that some love to hate, and
Brooks is warning his colleagues to avoid taking the power too
seriously.
   ``We cannot be smug about our leadership,'' Brooks says. ``We
don't know what kind of rapport you can work out with the
administration, and the problems are so big and the solutions are
going to be tough.''
</TEXT>
