<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Bhutto     12-04 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Bhutto,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistani Prime Minister Speaks Of Duties And Family</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pakistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan said
Sunday she has been too busy taking over the government to determine
whether documents exist shedding light on the death of her
predecessor or on Pakistan's nuclear capability.
   ``We haven't gone into these issues yet,'' Ms. Bhutto said in a
live television interview from Pakistan.
   She told British interviewer David Frost she has had other
priorities since being sworn into office on Friday, including naming
a Cabinet which was installed on Sunday.
   Ms. Bhutto, 35, also revealed that unspecified complications
resulted in her giving birth to a 7-pound son on Sept. 21 instead of
in October when he was due.
   It was widely believed in Pakistan that Ms. Bhutto tricked
President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq into calling elections for Nov. 16,
giving her time to recover from the birth and to resume campaigning.
Her family had let it be known the baby was not due until November
or December.
   ``I think the baby outwitted both of us,'' Ms. Bhutto said when
asked whether her son was premature or whether she had outwitted
Gen. Zia.
   ``The baby wasn't due until October, but because of certain
complications, he arrived in September.''
   Ms. Bhutto would not elaborate on the complications, but said her
son Bilawal was ``fine.''
   Zia died in a mysterious plane crash Aug. 17 after setting a date
for Pakistan's first free elections in more than a decade. Zia
overthrew the last civilian government led by Zulfikar Ali Bhutto,
Ms. Bhutto's father, in 1977, and two years later ordered his
execution.
   Authorities suspect sabotage in the crash, and a probe is
continuing.
   Ms. Bhutto, leader of the Pakistan People's Party, said that when
she took her oath of office Friday she could feel her father's
presence ``and sense his pride, not only in me, but in the success
of the whole party and in the success of democracy.''
   She said that if her father could advise her during her early
days as prime minister, ``first and foremost he would want me to be
my own person, because each one of us are judged on our own records,
not on the records of our famous forebearers.''
   Ms. Bhutto, who retained her maiden name following her arranged
marriage to businessman Asif Ali Zardari, said that motherhood has
meant changes.
   ``I start my day differently,'' she said. ``I go and see him (her
son) first thing. I end my day differently because I see him last
thing.''
   ``It's really nice to have a child,'' she said, adding ``It
doesn't sound very liberated, but a child does give much joy.''
   Asked whether she fears the army will attempt another coup in
Pakistan, Ms. Bhutto said, ``One cannot live on fears. One survives
on hopes.''
   Ms. Bhutto did not respond to questions of Pakistan's nuclear
capacity. Zia maintained the country had no program for producing an
atomic bomb, and used its facilities for enriching uranium _ a
process used to increase its radioacitivity _ only for peaceful
purposes. Outside experts, including U.S. officials, were skeptical.
</TEXT>
