<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dominican-Aliens     12-04 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican-Aliens,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>6 Dead, 5 Missing As Boatload of Illegal Immigrants Capsizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boat carrying 53 Dominicans trying
to illegally enter Puerto Rico capsized, killing six and leaving
five missing and presumed drowned, the U.S. Coast Guard said Sunday.
   The Coast Guard's Rescue Center in San Juan said the 25-foot
wooden boat capsized Saturday 18 miles west of Desecheo Island,
halfway between the Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico, while
transferring passengers to a Dominican Coast Guard vessel.
   The cutter USS Monhegan helped the Dominican ship rescue 42 of
the people who fell overboard, a duty officer at the rescue center
said. He said six were known to have drowned and five were missing.
   The search was called off at noon Sunday when no sign of the
missing was detected, the officer said.
   Reports from a Dominican navy spokesman and the Coast Guard's
Rescue Center indicate that the small boat sailed Saturday from a
beach on the northeastern coast of the Dominican Republic and was
spotted that night by a U.S. Coast Guard helicopter patrolling the
area.
   The USS Monhegan was sent to keep watch over the small craft
until the Dominican ship arrived and began to transfer the
passengers aboard.
   The patrols by the Dominican and U.S. Coast Guard units began
Saturday to search for a group of 27 Dominicans reported missing
since last week, when the boat on which they and 12 others traveled
was shipwrecked near Mona Island, located south of Desecheo. Twelve
were rescued, but the remaining 27 have not been found.
   The flow of Dominicans immigrating illegally to Puerto Rico in
small open boats has increased sharply in the last two weeks.
   In a five-day period that began Thanksgiving Day, 232 illegal
Dominican immigrants were caught in and around Puerto Rico's western
coast, the largest number arrested in Puerto Rico's history,
according to officials.
   But many others make it across the treacherous waters of the Mona
Passage.
   Border Patrol Chief Joe B. Bennett estimated only about 10
percent to 15 percent of those entering the island are caught. He
said 2,617 Dominican aliens have been arrested since April.
</TEXT>
