<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrivacyTown     12-04 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Privacy Town,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Residents Of Elite Community Want More Privacy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH OAKS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The locked gate that once guarded the
main road into this elite community is long gone, but some residents
want their privacy back, even suggesting ID armbands to identify
unwanted visitors.
   The 3,200 residents of the quiet, wooded community outside St.
Paul can legally make the world go away because everyone's property
extends to the middle of the road. With no no public streets,
residents can stop outsiders at the border.
   Residents maintain they aren't snobs. Rather, said Joan Brainard,
publisher of the North Oaks News and a former City Council member,
``We don't feel residents of other cities should willy-nilly be
using our facilities.''
   North Oaks has several lakes with beaches, tennis courts, hockey
rinks and soccer and football fields.
   The main entrance once had a locked gate; now there are four
entrances and Homeowners Association president William Ecklund said
installing security gates on them is not feasible because ``we've
got too many people out there.''
   A recent survey by the association, to which half its members
responded, found that 85 percent favor the use of ID decals on
residents' cars and 69 percent said decals should be on bicycles,
too.
   Some have gone so far as to suggest deputizing some residents who
could evict or arrest trespassers, but the board rejected the idea.
Member Sharon Anderson was turned off by the prospect of a
``vigilante group roaming the town.''
   Other suggestions that haven't gotten off the ground include
issuing residents armbands or ID cards.
   One resident, Connie Zmijewski, said she believes the town is
hurting itself by pushing for more privacy.
   She noted that last year a proposal to increase annual homeowners
association dues to build bicycle and walking paths was soundly
defeated after some opponents argued that the trails would attract
more outsiders.
   ``I'd hate to see park and recreation facilities not developed
because of our fear of others,'' she said. ``That's going
backwards.''
</TEXT>
