<HEAD>Mystery Woman To Testify in Suit Over Attack on Minister's Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE COCHRAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman identified as the lover of Walker Railey is
expected to testify Monday in a lawsuit accusing the former minister
of nearly strangling his wife, a lawyer for the wife's family says.
   Lucy Papillon has been ordered to testify in the case, said Bill
Arnold, the attorney for the family of Peggy Railey.
   Mrs. Railey was choked and left for dead in her garage in 1987.
The woman, then 38, is in what doctors have described as a
``persistent vegetative state'' in a nursing home.
   Ms. Papillon's alleged relationship with Railey became known last
year in a grand jury investigation of the attack.
   Railey, 41, former senior minister of the First United Methodist
Church, has been identified by police as a suspect in the case, but
no charges have been filed. Prosecutors have said the matter is
under investigation.
   Railey has denied trying to kill his wife and maintains he was
working on a research project at Southern Methodist University at
the time. He is believed to be living in California and is not
expected at Monday's proceedings.
   Ms. Papillon, a 46-year-old Dallas psychologist, has not publicly
discussed her relationship with Railey but sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity said she told a grand jury last year they had
been lovers since 1986.
   State District Judge John Whittington ruled last spring that
Railey, by refusing to respond to the lawsuit, technically admitted
the charges contained in the documents.
   He ``knowingly, maliciously and brutally attempted to strangle
his wife'' and cover up his actions with a ``false alibi,'' the
judge ruled.
   The civil case will decide how much in damages Mrs. Railey's
family is to receive.
