<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AngolaTalks     12-04 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola Talks,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Derailed Just As Agreement To Be Signed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban official said Sunday that the
sudden departure of South African diplomats derailed talks aimed at
peace in Angola and South-West Africa just as an agreement was about
to be signed.
   The South African delegation left Brazzaville on Saturday night
after four days of talks, saying it had to consult with its
government.
   Foreign Minister Pik Botha, who led the delegation, said the
talks ``could be resumed within a few days'' and a protocol signing
``is still a possibility.''
   But Cuban amd Angolan diplomats were reported to be angered by
the surprise departure of the South Africans after four days of
talks. Negotiators had hoped an interim treaty would be signed on
Saturday or Sunday, followed by a formal treaty ceremony in New York.
   The diplomats questioned South Africa's commitment to a
U.S.-mediated effort to negotiate the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban
troops from Angola and implementing U.N.-sponsored independence for
South-West Africa, also known as Namibia. The territory is
controlled by South Africa.
   ``If the South Africans were truly for peace in Angola and
independence in Namibia they would not have employed this diplomatic
ruse,'' said Ricardo de Quesada, Cuba's vice-minister for foreign
affairs.
   He said the diplomats were so close to agreement that the text
already had been typed.
   ``(The South Africans) have insulted everyone ... It is
legitimate to ask if they were negotiating seriously,`` de Quesada
said.
   He added, however: ``We think there is still a chance that we
will find ourselves back here in Brazzaville, but everything depends
on the contacts that are established by the mediator.''
   Chester Crocker, U.S. Assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, has been leading the negotiations.
   De Quesada's Angolan counterpart, Venancio de Moura, said Angola
and Cuban had been very flexible, ``but sadly we were treated
arrogantly by the South Africans.''
   The main obstacle to the agreeement has been the issue of how to
verify the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops, the first of which
arrived in Angola in 1976 to support the Marxist government. South
Africa has insisted on a Cuban pullout as a condition for granting
independence to South-West Africa, also known as Nambibia.
   The four sides have agreed to a 27-month timetable for a Cuban
withdrawal, but South Africa has demanded representation on the
force monitoring the withdrawal. Cuba and Angola have refused a
South African presence on the monitoring commission, saying the
United Nations will supervise the pullout.
   The Cuban troops have supported the Angolan government against
U.S.-aided rebels led by Jonas Savimbi, supported by South African
forces based in South-West Africa.
   De Moura on Sunday offered amnesty to the followers of the
guerrilla leader, who he said was responsible for ``the atrocities,
murders and destruction of the Angolan economy.'' But he said there
was ``no place for (Savimbi) in Angolan society.''
</TEXT>
