<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Soviet     12-04 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Soviet,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Says Normalization Process Under Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's top diplomat said Monday that his visit to
the Soviet Union was the first step toward thawing three decades of
chilly relations.
   ``We both believe a summit is possible but we still have to talk
about a specific date,'' Foreign Minister Qian Qichen told reporters
upon arriving at the Beijing airport. ``We must make serious
preparations.''
   Qian flew from Tokyo, where he had briefed Japanese officials on
his three-day visit to Moscow that ended Saturday.
   Qian's visit to Moscow, during which he held two hours of talks
with Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev and more than six hours of
talks with Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze, was the first by a
Chinese foreign minister since 1957.
   He invited Shevardnadze to visit Beijing early next year but said
an exact date was not set.
   Both sides have said that a summit between Gorbachev and senior
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping could take place in the first half of
1989. Chinese and Soviet sources agree late April or May is the most
likely time.
   ``The most important result was we started the normalization
process,'' Qian told reporters as he walked from the plane to a
waiting limousine.
   He said talks focused on normalizing relations and the main
obstacle _ Soviet-allied Vietnam's 10-year occupation of Cambodia.
China maintains that Soviet aid is essential to the Vietnamese
occupation and wants Moscow to pressure Vietnam to pull out.
   Qian said the Soviet Union had agreed to do so. Asked if this was
a new position on Moscow's part, he said, ``You can understand it
that way.''
   ``Both China and the Soviet Union should play a role,'' he added.
   Qian said he and the Soviets discussed in general terms a
timetable for Vietnamese withdrawal and came closer together on this
issue. He refused to elaborate. China has said the Vietnamese should
pull out as soon as possible.
   Asked if all differences over Cambodia had to be resolved before
a summit was possible, Qian said simply, ``We must continue
discussions.''
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and toppled the
Chinese-allied Khmer Rouge, which had killed an estimated 1 million
fellow Cambodians in an effort to purge the country of all modern
influences. China is the main supporter of a guerrilla coalition,
including the Khmer Rouge, fighting the Vietnamese.
   China's two other requirements for normalizing relations with
Moscow are a Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan and reduction of
Soviet troops along the Chinese border. The Soviet Union has pulled
half of its more than 100,000 troops out of Afghanistan but halted
the process recently.
   It has cut slightly its troop presence in allied Mongolia,
adjoining China, and China and the Soviet Union have resolved part
of their border dispute.
   The Communist giants were close allies in the 1950s but split in
the early 1960s because of ideological and strategic differences
between Mao Tse-tung and Nikita Khruschev. Troops clashed along the
border in 1969.
   Trade, cultural and other non-political exchanges have grown
rapidly in the past few years as both countries have focused less on
ideology and more on economic development.
</TEXT>
