<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Walesa     12-04 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Walesa,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Wants Close Adviser On First Trip Abroad In Seven Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on Sunday
insisted that one of his closest advisers be allowed to accompany
him to France on his first trip abroad in seven years.
   French President Francois Mitterrand invited Walesa to Paris to
attend the Dec. 10 celebrations of the 40th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
   Referring to historian Bronislaw Geremek, one of his closest
advisers, Walesa said: ``His company is necessary for me, not only
because he speaks French. There's just a very short time to prepare
myself and I need his help.'' ``Lech is insisting that I go,'' said
Geremek, who said the Solidarity leader asked him on Saturday to
make the trip.
   Geremek, who said he will make the request for a passport on
Monday, said he has been refused permission to travel abroad on five
separate occasions recently.
   Walesa said he had applied for a passport last week and was
informed on Saturday he could pick it up on Monday.
   The trip represents the first time the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize
winner has been given permission to leave Poland since the
imposition of martial law on Dec. 13, 1981.
   Polish citizens must apply for a passport each time they wish to
travel to a Western country. Travel restrictions have been eased in
recent years, although some passports still are denied for political
reasons.
   In March, Walesa was barred from making a trip to Australia
because the government said it did not want him to attend an
international trade union conference.
   Walesa helped found Solidarity, which was the only recognized
labor federation in the Soviet bloc. It was banned in 1981 and
outlawed the following year.
</TEXT>
