<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-04 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Blankets Lower Great Lakes Region, Northern Appalachians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   While much of the nation enjoyed fair weather Sunday, squalls
continued to bring light snow to the lower Great Lakes region.
   Two to 5 inches of snow was expected in western New York State
southeast of lakes Erie and Ontario, and in western Mohawk Valley of
upstate New York.
   Up to a foot of snow blanketed higher elevations of Vermont by
Sunday morning.
   A cold front produced snow in the northern Appalachians, with 2
inches reported at Mount Washington, N.H., during the six hours up
to 1 p.m. EST. At noon, Mount Washington was reporting light snow
and fog, with 80 mph wind gusts and a temperature of 6 degrees below
zero.
   Strong northwest winds behind the cold front produced the snow
squalls in the lower Great Lakes region. Gale warnings were posted
for Lake Ontario and for the Atlantic coast from Delaware to Maine.
   Fog covered valleys west of the Rocky Mountains as a high
pressure area hovered over the western two-thirds of the country.
   Scattered light rain showers lingered over south-central Texas,
and clouds were prevalent from the northern high Plains through the
middle and upper Mississippi Valley into the Great Lakes region.
Most of the rest of the nation had fair to partly sunny skies.
   Freezing temperatures were primarily confined to the Northeast on
Sunday afternoon. Temperatures were generally in the 50s and 60s
from the Rio Grande Valley of Texas to the southern Atlantic Coast,
with 70s in southern Florida and south-central and southeastern
Texas. Temperatures were mostly in the 60s and 70s in Southern
California and southern Arizona, with readings above 80 at some
locations.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 19
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 84 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
The nation's low Sunday morning was 9 degrees below zero at
Gunnison, Colo.
   The National Weather Service forecast scattered snow showers
Monday in the lower Great Lakes region, rain in western Washington
and scattered rain showers in the rest of the Pacific Northwest.
   Temperatures were expected to remain below 40 degrees from
northern Minnesota to northern New England, with highs in the 20s in
northern New England and upstate New York and teens across northern
Maine. Highs were predicted to be in the 30s in the high country
west of the central Rockies, above 60 from the southern and central
California coast to southern Arizona, in the 70s in extreme southern
California and extreme southern Arizona. Temperatures also should
exceed 60 from Florida to central Oklahoma and central Texas, with
70s across southern Florida.
</TEXT>
