<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     12-04 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kosovo Communists Defy Republic's Leaders, Don't Condemn Rallies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist officials in a restive
province of the Serbian Republic on Sunday rejected calls by
Serbia's leaders to condemn recent mass rallies in the region.
   An extraordinary plenum of the Communist Party in Kosovo province
was convened to assess the largest-ever demonstrations two weeks ago
by the ethnic Albanian majority in the province.
   The rallies were staged to protest the resignation of two ethnic
Albanian leaders of the province who were forced to resign under
pressure.
   Serbian Communist leader Slobodan Milosevic is seeking to curtail
the autonomy of Kosovo to protect the Slav minority allegedly
persecuted by ethnic Albanians, who make up a 90 percent of Kosovo's
population.
   Serbian leaders also insist that the demonstrations were
``counterrevolutionary,'' a qualification apparently rejected by
Sunday's session in Pristina, the capital of Kosovo.
   Djumret Seljami, an ethnic Albanian leader addressing the
meeting, insisted that ``the mass rallies of citizens of Albanian
nationality, in their initial days ... essentially expressed
Socialist and Yugoslav orientation.''
   But in his comments, quoted by the state news agency Tanjug,
Saljami acknowledged that the rallies assumed a more hostile tone in
the final days.
   Up to 100,000 people took to the streets to protest the dismissal
of former and current Presidium members Azem Vlasi and Kacusa Jasari.
   In another development, newspapers dsaid Sunday that two ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo had been sentenced to 45 and 60 days
imprisonment respectively for making threats against Milosevic.
   The Belgrade daily Politika said Enver Peci, 37, of the Kosovo
town of Vucitrn, was given 60 days by the local magistrate for
publicly stating that the ammunition he had in his pocket was for
use against Milosevic.
   The other defendant, 22-year-old Ljutvi Vanuzi, also of Vucitrn,
was sentenced for shouting in the local post office: ``Long live
(fired leaders) Jasari and Vlasi, death to Slobodan Milosevic.''
   In a related report, Politika said two ethnic Albanian farmers
near the Kosovo town of Decani were sentenced to two months each for
singing songs praising Enver Hoxha, the late leader of neighboring
Communist Albania.
   Thousands of Albanians have been sent to jail for demanding
greater autonomy for Kosovo.

</TEXT>
