<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   12-04 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0678,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Born Settler Sentenced To Three Years As Unrest Continues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 5th, `A military...' to UPDATE with
grenade attack; picks up 6th pvs: The 1.5...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Sunday sentenced an American-born
immigrant to three years in prison for the shooting death of an Arab
shepherd who brought his sheep to graze near a Jewish settlement in
the occupied West Bank.
   The Jerusalem court last week convicted Israel Zeev of
manslaughter in the fatal May shooting. It was the first time a
Jewish civilian was convicted in the death of an Arab since the
start of the nearly yearlong Palestinian uprising.
   Zeev, 38, a Chicago native who moved to Israel more than 20 years
ago, also was convicted of shooting and seriously injuring a second
Arab.
   In the occupied territories Sunday, troops raided five West Bank
villages and rounded up suspected Arab protesters, Arab reports
said. At least eight Palestinians, most of them teenagers, were shot
and wounded in scattered clashes, hospital officials said.
   A military spokesman said he was checking the reports.
   In the West Bank town of Hebron, a hand grenade thrown at an
Israeli public bus exploded on the road and caused no injuries, the
army said. It exploded on the road, causing no injuries or damage.
Suspects were arrested, the Israeli news agency Itim said.
   The 1.5 million Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip have been engaged in a revolt against Israeli rule since Dec.
8, 1987. Israel captured the Gaza Strip from Egypt and the West Bank
from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Eleven Israelis and 318 Palestinians have been killed in the
uprising.
   Of the eight Arabs wounded Sunday, five were shot in the occupied
Gaza Strip, two were wounded in Nablus, the largest city in the
occupied West Bank, and one was shot in the West Bank village of
Awarta, hospital officials said.
   In annexed East Jerusalem, District Court Judge Zvi Cohen
sentenced Zeev to a two-year suspended sentence in addition to three
years in prison, and ordered him to pay the family of the dead Arab,
28-year-old Jude Abdallah Awad, about $17,500 in compensation. The
sum is the maximum amount allowed by Israeli law.
   Zeev's defense attorney, Jacob Weinroth, said he would probably
appeal the conviction.
   ``All along the main thing that has bothered my client in
principle was the fact that he killed a man,'' Weinroth said.
   After Zeev's sentencing, settlers from Shilo, 18 miles north of
Jerusalem, rose to shake his hand.
   Zeev, wearing jeans and the large knitted skullcap that is a
trademark of observant Jews, said nothing but appeared somewhat
relieved.
   Fellow settlers said they objected to the sentence, claiming Zeev
was merely doing his duty guarding the settlement and should have
been tried in a military rather than civil court. They vowed to
raise the compensation money. Arabs said District Court Judge Zvi
Cohen's sentence was too light.
   ``The sentence is very light,'' said Odeh Rantisi, former deputy
mayor of Ramallah, north of Jerusalem. ``This means disrespect for
life given by God. This is the law of the jungle, where the strong
kill the weak.''
   The maximum sentence for manslaughter is 20 years. But Zeev said
the Arab shepherds ignored his orders to leave the area and hurled
rocks at him when he fired warning shots in the air.
   Zeev, in jail for seven months since the killing occurred, will
have that period deducted from his sentence and will probably
qualify to get one-third of the term reduced for good behavior,
Weinroth said. He could be eligible for parole in 19 months.
</TEXT>
