<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Gorbachev     12-04 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Gorbachev,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets May Talk Human Rights During Gorbachev Stop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union may raise the issue of human
rights in Britain during next week's talks between President Mikhail
Gorbachev and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, a Soviet spokesman
said Sunday.
   ``I think simply a human rights question is a two-way street, and
charity begins at home,'' said Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman
Gennady I. Gerasimov in an interview from New York with Independent
Television News. ``If you discuss our human rights problems, we can
also raise certain questions.''
   Gerasimov was interviewed after The Mail on Sunday, a weekly
tabloid, said the Soviets would attack Britain's human rights
record, especially in dealing with Irish terrorism suspects.
   The tabloid, which supports Mrs. Thatcher's Conservative
government, said Gorbachev had authorized ``a propaganda blitz''
that could include a meeting with families of Irish people convicted
of bombings in Britain. The Irish Republican Army is waging a
military campaign to oust the British from Northern Ireland and
reunite it with the Irish Republic.
   However, Gerasimov said the Soviets had no plans to embarrass
Mrs. Thatcher over the human rights issue during Gorbachev's Dec.
12-14 visit on his three-nation tour.
   Before going to Britain, Gorbachev is to arrive in New York on
Tuesday and in Cuba on Friday.
   During Mrs. Thatcher's visit to the Soviet Union last year, she
held talks with dissident Nobel Prize winner Andrei Sakharov and
gave Gorbachev at list of individual human rights cases of concern
to Britain.
   Mrs. Thatcher's aides said the prime minister normally raises
human rights issues in the Soviet Union when she meets Gorbachev and
would probably do so during next week's meeting.
   British commentators said that if Gorbachev raises the cases of
Irish men and women jailed for fatal pub bombings in Birmingham,
Woolwich and Guildford in 1974, Mrs. Thatcher will tell him that
their rights have been protected in a series of trials and appeals.
   Chris Mullin, a lawmaker from the opposition Labor Party who has
led a campaign to prove the innocence of the convicted people, said
he was writing to Soviet Ambassador Leonid Zamyatin to offer to
arrange for Gorbachev to be briefed on the cases.
   ``I welcome the news that Mr. Gorbachev may raise with Mrs.
Thatcher the case of the six innocent men convicted of the
Birmingham pub bombings and the total of 11 innocent people
convicted in connection with the Guildford and Woolwich pub
bombings,'' he said.
   Patrick McIlkenny, the brother of one of the men convicted in the
Birmingham bombings, said a meeting with Gorbachev would give ``an
extra boost'' to his brother's spirits, Independent Television News
reported. McIlkenny recently visited Moscow and met one of
Gorbachev's senior foreign affairs advisers.
   The six men were convicted of two IRA pub bombings that killed 21
people. A total of seven died in the attacks in Guilford and
Woolwich.
</TEXT>
