<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Stock Prices Also Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slipped slightly against the Japanese yen
at the start of the trading week Monday, while stock prices also
declined moderately.
   The dollar opened trading at 121.48 yen, down 0.16 yen from
Friday's close of 121.64 yen.
   The slide in the U.S. currency followed dollar-buying in the
Sydney market after news that ailing Japanese Emperor Hirohito took
a turn for the worse, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
   ``The news of the emperor lingered a bit in the Tokyo market and
the dollar was sold off'' in the absence of other fresh news, added
the dealer, speaking anonymously.
   Hirohito, bedridden since Sept. 19 with internal hemorrhaging,
discharged a large amount of blood early Monday morning and was
given an emergency blood transfusion.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues toppled from its record closing figure of 29,665.50
points reached Saturday. It shed 104.64 points, or 0.3 percent,
shortly after the market opened to move to 29,560.86.
