<HEAD>Sakharov to Visit Paris For Human Rights Celebration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet dissident physicist Andrei Sakharov will
stop in Paris to attend a celebration of the 40th anniversary of the
Declaration of Human Rights after he ends his visit to the United
States, a relative said Sunday.
   ``On his way to Moscow, he will stop in Paris for a few days at
the invitation of the French president,'' said Efrem Yankelevich,
Sakharov's stepdaughter's husband.
   Yankelevich said the visit would change Sakharov's schedule but
said he and family members were unsure when the Soviet human rights
activist would leave or when he would arrive in Moscow.
   Sakharov arrived in the United States a month ago.
   During his stay, Sakharov has undergone medical tests in Boston,
visited New York and Washington, where he met President Reagan, and
spent Thanksgiving at the suburban Boston home of Yankelevich and
his wife, Tatiana, who is the daughter of Sakharov's wife, Yelena
Bonner.
   The universal Declaration of Human Rights was passed by the
United Nations on Dec. 10, 1948, and spells out fundamental human
rights. The date is observed each year as international human rights
day around the world.
