<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PershingDestruction     12-04 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pershing Destruction,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Inspectors Arrive For Missile Burn</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PBO1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten inspectors from the Soviet Union arrived
here Sunday to monitor the burning of Pershing rocket motors at an
Army depot under terms of a nuclear arms reduction treaty.
   The burn was scheduled to begin Monday, weather permitting. The
state health department allows the Army to burn only six rockets per
day, and only when the wind is at least 4 mph from the west.
   Pueblo Army Depot Activity spokesman Alan Kenitzer said 18 rocket
motors probably will be burned this month.
   Similar burns have been taking place since Sept. 8 at the
Longhorn Army Ammunition Plant near Marshall, Texas.
   The Pershings were the delivery systems for European-based
nuclear warheads aimed at the Soviet Union. Under terms of the
intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty that took effect June 1,
the United States has two years to destroy 450 of the missiles, each
of which is propelled by two rocket motors.
   In exchange, the Soviet Union will destroy a larger number of
their medium-range missiles as U.S. inspectors look on.
   Kenitzer said the Soviet inspectors arrived in Pueblo on Sunday
from Travis Air Force Base, Calif. They proceeded to the depot,
about 10 miles east of the city, for a briefing and to mark the
motors to be eliminated, he said.
   They will check for the marks again immediately before the burns
to make sure those motors are the ones destroyed.
</TEXT>
