<2ND_LINE>AM-Trains Collide, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0760,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Dead, 85 Injured in Commuter Train Crash
^Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with one more dead, details,
background on pvs train crashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commuter train slammed into another train stopped
at a Tokyo station on Monday, killing two people and injuring about
85, authorities said.
   The impact crushed parts of the two cars and derailed several
cars, police said. About 600 people were reported on board the two
trains.
   The collision occurred about 9:40 a.m. (7:40 p.m. EST) at the
Higashi-Nakano Station on the Sobu Line, one of Japan Railways'
surface commuter lines. The station is two stops west of Shinjuku
Station, a major railway and commuter line juncture in west-central
Tokyo.
   The cause of the crash was unknown, but news reports said
westbound trains were running about 10 minutes behind schedule when
one of them smashed into the rear of another west-bound train
stopped in the Higashi-Nakano station.
   A male passenger and the driver of the moving train, 28-year-old
Teruki Hirao, were killed, said a police official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Fire and police officials said about 85 people were injured. The
police official who spoke on condition of anonymity said 10 were in
serious condition.
   Fire department rescue teams worked to free people from the
crushed cars. Dazed but injured survivors were rushed to nearby
hospitals.
   Keiko Uehara, who runs a bookstore near the Higashi-Nakano
Station, said the crash made such a noise that ``I thought a
building had fallen down.''
   The accident was the first causing injuries on Tokyo commuter
trains since March 1986, when about 60 people were hurt in the
collision of two trains.
   The last previous fatal accident was in December 1984, when a
train driver was killed and at least 120 people injured in the
head-on collision of two trains.
</TEXT>
