<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Venezuela 4thLd-Writethru   12-04 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuela, 4th Ld - Writethru,a0749,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perez Elected To Five-Year Term</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix writethru sequence; LEADS with 20 grafs
to UPDATE with congressional projections, background; picks up 19th
pvs: The new...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carlos Andres Perez
was elected to a five-year term on Sunday, returning to the office
he held a decade ago by focusing on the prosperity of the past.
   The Supreme Electoral Council declared that Perez, based on small
early returns, would win the election over his main opponent,
conservative Eduardo Fernandez of the Social Christian Party.
   Perez previously served from 1974 to 1979. By law, a president
may not to return to office for 10 years.
   Perez, 66, is to succeed President Jaime Lusinchi, also a member
of the Democratic Action party.
   The victory gives the left-of-center party two consecutive
victories during this wealthy oil-exporting nation's worst economic
crisis in decades.
   Perez also becomes the first president to win a second term since
the ouster of military rule in 1958.
   ``This is the point of departure for building a bigger Venezuela.
The next government must take advantage of our situation to form the
bases for future growth,'' Perez said on national television.
   Fernandez, 48, conceded defeat within minutes after the council's
announcement.
   ``I offer (Perez) constructive but firm opposition that will put
the interests of Venezuela above particular interests,'' Fernandez
said on television.
   The first report from the elections council, based on only 1,919
votes, gave Perez 914 votes, or 47.6 percent. It said Fernandez had
811 votes, or 42.2 percent. The elections council, however, declared
Perez the winner.
   Perez was forecast the winner hours earlier by the major
television networks, which gave the former president a huge lead
based on exit polls.
   Venevision projected nearly 3.9 million votes for Perez, or 54.1
percent, to 2.7 million for Fernandez, or 33.7 percent.
   No official tallies were given on the outcome of voting for the
all-new National Congress of 182 deputies and 44 senators, but the
private networks projected the Democratic Action party would win
48.6 percent and the Social Christians 26.3 percent in both houses.
   Voting is mandatory in Venezuela, but private projections
projected that 15 percent of the 9 million eligible voters did not
cast ballots.
   A high abstention rate was widely predicted because of general
voter dissatisfaction with both major candidates.
   Perez is closely identified with the good economic times of the
1970s, when the Arab oil embargo helped stimulate rapid growth and
prosperity. He nationalized foreign oil holdings in Venezuela during
his presidency.
   His previous five-year term was dogged by charges of corruption,
however.
   Perez, a charismatic figure popular with the working class,
favors tighter state control over the economy. Fernandez favors a
freer market.
   There are 23 other presidential candidates on the ballot, but
none was given a chance to beat either of the two big parties.
   Lusinchi's five-year term was one of economic decline in a
country battered by the drop in oil prices. Oil makes up 90 percent
of the country's exports.
   The new president, to be inaugurated in February, will face
growing poverty in what has been Latin America's richest nation. The
standard of living is still one of the highest in the region but it
has been reduced by inflation and devaluations since 1982.
   Since 1984, the nation's income from oil was halved to an
expected $7.1 billion this year, while foreign debt payments have
continued at a rate of about $5 billion a year during Lusinchi's
term. The debt stands at $33 billion.
   The depressed economic climate helped lead to one of the most
unenthusiastic campaigns in Venezuela's 30 years of democracy.
Public rallies drew mainly the party faithful.
   In addition to their financial woes, voters have also been
disenchanted with widesread corruption in government and the
perception that neither Perez nor Fernandez will do anything about
it.
   Perez promised price controls and wage increases. He also called
for ``selective economic growth'' by pushing non-oil exports such as
gold, aluminum, and steel.
</TEXT>
