<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Occupations     12-04 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Occupations,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beleaguered Michoacan Governor To Leave For Federal Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDAJOY FENLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters who seized dozens of city halls
celebrated Sunday after President Carlos Salinas de Gortari removed
a state governor whose ouster they had demanded.
   Salinas gave Michoacan state Gov. Luis Martinez Villacina a new
job as director of Federal Toll Highways and Bridges, the Excelsior
news service reported Saturday. As such, he will be in charge of
collecting tolls on federal highways.
   Leftist protesters, who backed the leading rival to Salinas in
July presidential elections, took control of about 30 Michoacan city
halls on Nov. 26 to demand the ouster of Martinez Villacina. He
belongs to the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party.
   The protestors from the National Democratic Front, a coalition
that supported Cuauhtemoc Cardenas for president, said Martinez
Villacina had ``squandered the public treasury'' and ``fomented
political hatred'' in the north central state.
   Demonstrators at city hall in the provincial city of Uruapan were
jubilant Sunday that the governor was gone, said protester Uriel
Lopez Paredes. ``We set off firecrackers and danced. We had a
party.''
   A red ribbon was tied around city hall, but Francisco Curi Perez
said that the 100 people still inside planned to stay. Curi Perez, a
federal deputy for the Democratic Front, said the demonstrators want
at least four mayors in the region who belong to the governing party
to resign.
   ``They used government funds for (Institutional Revolutionary
Party) candidates,'' he said.
   Although federal police peacefully evicted protestors from 25
city halls within the first two days of the protests, activists
still occupied several city halls during the weekend. Many were also
pressing local issues and had vowed to remain, like those of Uruapan.
   However, Democratic Front Senator Christobal Arias Solis said
Salinas' decision to name Martinez Villacina to a federal post could
end the state's political battle, Excelsior reported.
   The Michoacan state Congress is expected to name the interim
governor Monday or Tuesday, according to Excelsior. Meanwhile,
Genovevo Figueroa, state secretary-general, will act as governor.
   Arias Solis said the new governor should either be a supporter of
Cardenas or ``at least someone who will govern for all the people,''
the news service reported.
   Michoacan voters in July supported Cardenas, a former Michoacan
state governor who came in second to Salinas.
   Salinas, elected with the narrowest margin of victory in the
governing party's 59-year history, was inaugurated Thursday.
Cardenas has been challenging the election results, which he says
are fraudulent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
