<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Ames-Zayre     12-04 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ames-Zayre,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ames Expected To Close 74 Zayre Stores, Chiefly In Southern States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Ames Department Stores Inc. is expected to close about 75 of the
392 Zayre discount store outlets it purchased in September,
published reports said.
   The Boston Globe and the Hartford Courant said the closings of
the stores, which were described as unprofitable, were to be
announced Monday.
   Rosemary Keogh O'Neill, a spokeswoman for the Rocky Hill,
Conn.-based Ames, said the company would not confirm or deny the
reports.
   Most of the stores earmarked for closing are in Georgia,
Louisiana, South Carolina, Tennessee and Alabama, along with six in
Wisconsin. Ames, of Rocky Hill, Conn., is closing three of its own
outlets, leaving a total of 840 combined stores.
   Zayre Corp. sold its discount store division to Ames in September
for $775 million. The stores had been losing money for some time.
   The deal left Zayre with two divisions, the TJX Cos., which
includes the T.J. Maxx, Hit or Miss and Chadwick's stores, and the
wholesale division, which includes B.J.'s Wholesale Club and
HomeClub.
</TEXT>
