<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HarrisLayoffs     12-04 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harris Layoffs,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harris Corp. Fires 280, More Layoffs Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harris Corp., which recently bought the
semi-conductor business of General Electric Co., has laid off 280
workers and offered severance packages to thousands of other
employees.
   The layoffs, which total about 4 percent of the 6,500 workers at
Harris' Government Systems Sector here, were hastened by the
high-tech company's loss of a contract t develop the Tracking and
Data Relay Satellite System ground terminal for NASA.
   But company spokesman James Murphy said the firings announced
Friday were the result of the slowdown in expected military business.
   Securities analysts have speculated at least 800 jobs would be
eliminated overall in the first wave of layoffs following Harris
$206 million purchase of GE's solid state semiconductor business.
   The semiconductor division lost $30 million in the year ended
June 30 and $11.9 million in the following quarter.
   The merger, completed Nov. 30, made Harris the nation's
sixth-largest semiconductor company.
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. telecommunications analyst Maria
Lewis said she expected Harris to announce one or more plant
closings early next year and a staff reduction of at least 10
percent.
   The company's semiconductor operation employing 8,000 people is
based here and has facilities in Findlay, Ohio, Mountaintop, Pa.,
and Santa Clara, Calif. The corporation employs 33,000 worldwide.
   ``Mergers of this magnitude inevitably involve substantial
organizational changes and adjustments to head count,'' said Jon E.
Cornell, senior vice president of Harris Semiconductor Sector.
   The layoffs are mostly a reflection of Harris management's
reluctance to sacrifice profits for the payroll, Ms. Lewis said,
noting that John T. Hartley, chairman and chief executive officer,
has pledged to stockholders to keep profits rising at double-digit
rates even while sales gains are modest.
</TEXT>
