<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SundstrandChanges     12-04 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sundstrand Changes,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chairman Will Retire At Company Tied To Defense Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Sundstrand Corp. is
stepping down less than two months after the company agreed to pay a
record $127.3 million in fines for overcharging the government on
defense contracts.
   Evans W. Erikson, 62, once listed by Forbes magazine as one of
the most powerful industrial executives in the nation, said Friday
he is retiring from the aerospace-products manufacturer to ``pursue
personal interests.''
   Erikson, a 36-year veteran of Sundstrand, will leave the company
at the end of December.
   Erikson's positions as chairman and chief executive officer will
be split between two of his top deputies.
   Don R. O'Hare, 66, vice chairman through Erikson's eight years in
command, moves up to chairman, while Harry C. Stonecipher, 52,
president and chief operating officer, who came to Sundstrand from
General Electric Co. two years ago, will serve as chief executive
officer.
   In a separate release issued at the same time, Erikson announced
he has promoted corporate Treasurer Paul Donovan, 41, who joined the
company in June, to vice president of finance.
   ``Now that the company has resolved the criminal investigation of
its government contracting practices, it is an appropriate time for
me to pursue personal interests,'' Erikson said in a statement.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Keith Syfert said a grand jury is still
considering possible indictments against some company officials. He
declined to say if Erikson's resignation is related to the
investigation.
   Sundstrand, which manufactures electronic, mechanical and
hydraulic systems for the government and civilian aerospace
industries, has 14,500 employees at 19 sites in various states.
   In an apparently unrelated move, the company also confirmed that
it had laid off another 32 office employees as part of a
restructuring move that has been going on for the past year.
   The company said that more than 300 white-collar employees have
been laid off since last December.
   In its recent third-quarter report to stockholders, Sundstrand
warned them to brace for a possible $39.2 million in penalties the
federal government might levy on top of the $127 million the company
has already agreed to pay.
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas recently said the additional fines
apparently would involve civil issues that were not resolved by the
settlement of criminal charges filed by the government.
   Sundstrand pleaded guilty earlier this year in Rockford to four
counts of defrauding the Defense Department by overbilling on
aircraft parts. It also pleaded guilty in Seattle to mischarging on
government contracts.
   In the October plea agreement, Sundstrand also admitted to
lavishing gifts and gratuities on government employees and military
personnel involved in its contract bidding, as well as billing the
government for trips and other perks of company executives. No names
have been divulged.
   The Pentagon suspended the company from bidding on government
contracts after it admitted to engaging in the largest military
fraud in U.S. history.
   In addition, the State Department reportedly is delaying approval
of export licenses required to send Sundstrand products overseas.
</TEXT>
