<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Alcoa-Reynolds-Steelworkers     12-04 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alcoa-Reynolds-Steelworkers,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steelworkers, Aluminum Companies Reach `Historic' Tentative
Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the United Steelworkers of
America and Alcoa and Reynolds Metals reached a tentative agreement
over the weekend on a 3{-year contract that includes a first-ever
profit-sharing plan for 9,300 workers.
   The contract, subject to a Dec. 9 rank-and-file vote, also offers
the largest salary and benefits package in the recent history of the
aluminum industry, officials said Saturday.
   The 43-month contract would take effect June 1, 1989, after the
current contract expires.
   ``This contract reflects improvements in the companies' profits
and the success that they're enjoying,'' union spokesman Gary
Hubbard, who spoke by phone from the union's headquarters in
Pittsburgh. ``We're confident our members will approve it.''
   Alcoa, based in Pittsburgh, employs 6,000 steelworkers union
members at six plants in North Carolina, Tennessee, Texas and
Arkansas.
   Reynolds' 3,300 employees work at plants in Virginia, Arkansas,
Texas, Missouri, Illinois, Washington state and Florida.
   Both companies are rebounding from a six-year struggle against
weak world aluminum prices, which rose this year to $1.12 a pound
after plunging to about 45 cents a pound in 1986, Alcoa spokesman
Alfred Posti said.
   Alcoa underwent a massive restructuring from 1983 to 1985 that
involved reducing its worldwide smelting operations by 25 percent,
he said.
   But this year, ``it should be a record year, no doubt about it,''
Posti said.
   Reynolds is likely to gross a record $5 billion in sales in 1988,
said spokesman William Conley.
   The pact was hammered out during three days of talks in
Cincinnati.
   The profit-sharing plan would allow workers to receive a share of
the company's profits if earnings exceed a specified return of
stockholder equity, Posti said. The plan would net workers about
$2,500 each for 1988, he said.
   The new contract also calls for a wage increase of 50
cents-per-hour, Hubbard said.
   In 1986, when the benchmark price for aluminum plunged to about
45 cents a pound, Alcoa and Reynolds steelworkers agreed to a
95-cent-an-hour pay cut, he said.
</TEXT>
