<DOCNO> AP881204-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-88 1752EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HiringPlans     12-04 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hiring Plans,0279</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hiring Will Remain Strong in First Quarter, Survey Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey of U.S. firms released on Sunday found
they planned to keep on hiring new workers at a strong pace during
the first quarter.
   The survey, conducted by Manpower Inc., a temporary employment
agency, found 22 percent of nearly 14,000 employers planned to
increase hiring from January through March, while 64 percent said
there would be no change in their plans and 11 percent said they
would decrease hiring.
   The respondents included private companies and government
agencies.
   A year ago, 21 percent of the respondents planned to increase
hiring, and 12 percent said they would decrease it during the first
quarter of 1988.
   On Friday, the Labor Department said the unemployment rate rose
to 5.4 percent in November from October's 5.3 percent. The
government also reported 463,000 new jobs were created, indicating
the economy continues to be robust.
   Manpower said hiring demand appeared to be strong in all
industries except in construction and wholesale and retail trade.
However, the survey found the seasonal drop in hiring in wholesale
and retail trade, which follows the Christmas holidays, would be
less than usual.
   The survey also found hiring demand was strong in the South and
West while dipping slightly in the Northeast from the levels of
first quarter 1988. Demand improved in the Midwest, Manpower said.
   Manpower conducts the survey of employers' hiring plans
quarterly. The latest survey was conducted by telephone during the
last two weeks of November, and queried employers in 423 cities
across the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
