<1ST_LINE>u s AM-BKC--CarrierClassic-La.Tech-Syracuse 1stLd-Writethru
  12-04 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BKC--Carrier Classic-La. Tech-Syracuse, 1st Ld-Writethru,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Optional</HEAD>
<HEAD>Syracuse 106, La. Tech 98</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syracuse grabbed its typical big lead
against Louisiana Tech, but this time it nearly cost the Orangemen
their own tournament.
   ``We went ahead 22-3 and thought we had them. That's the worst
thing a player can do,'' said Syracuse forward Stephen Thompson
after the fourth-ranked Orangemen held off Louisiana Tech in
overtime to take a 106-98 victory Sunday in the 12th annual Carrier
Classic.
   ``When you let a good team like that back into the game, it
builds their confidence. Once they got confident, they were hard to
stop,'' said Thompson, who led Syracuse with 25 points.
   Guard Matt Roe agreed that Syracuse's 23-point lead in the first
half almost proved to be its downfall.
   ``I think we rested on our laurels and coasted some,'' said Roe,
who also had 25 points.
   ``But I think our defense broke down and Derrick (Coleman)
getting into foul trouble didn't help,'' he added.
   Coleman sparked Syracuse's triumph, scoring six of his 23 points
in the overtime period.
   ``I wanted to play great defense and help out offensively. I
don't like losing. I was determined to make sure we gutted it out,''
said Coleman, who also had 14 rebounds.
   Louisiana Tech senior center Randy White said the key to the
Bulldogs' comeback was when Coleman went to the bench four minutes
into the second half with his fourth personal foul.
   ``We didn't do a good job early, they were getting easy buckets
and threw off our rhythym,'' White said. ``That's the thing about us
_ we don't give up. But the main key was to get Coleman out of the
ballgame.''
   Louisiana Tech forward Byron Newton sent the game into overtime
with a 3-point shot as time expired in regulation play. Newton's
shot came after Coleman missed the front end of a 1-and-1 with five
seconds to play.
   Syracuse won the tournament for the 10th time and improved its
record to 7-0. Louisiana Tech fell to 3-1.
   The Orangemen hit their first 11 shots, racing to a 24-5 lead,
and appeared headed for another easy game. Syracuse built a 35-12
cushion midway through the half and took a 54-36 lead at halftime.
   But Louisiana Tech outscored Syracuse 23-11 in the opening five
minutes of the second half to cut the deficit to 65-59 with 15:20 to
play.
   White then took over for the Bulldogs, keeping them close with
his 20 second-half points. White finished with 29 points before
fouling out with five seconds to play.
   Coleman, playing with four personals, kept Syracuse in the lead
with several clutch shots, but missed the free throw that could have
clinched the game for the Orangemen.
   Thompson and Roe led Syracuse with 25 points apiece. Roe scored
five of his points in overtime.
   Senior guard Darryl Knight had 23 points for Louisiana Tech,
while Newton finished with 17.
</TEXT>
