<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GasPrices 1stLd-Writethru   12-04 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gas Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Price Drops To Under $1 For First Time Since Early July</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 2nd reference to regular unleaded in 8th graf to
regular leaded.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Average gasoline prices at pumps across the
nation decreased almost half a cent in the past two weeks, dropping
to under $1 for the first time since early July, an analyst said
Sunday.
   The Lundberg Survey, a sampling of 12,000 service stations
nationwide, found the average retail price of gasoline was 99.61
cents on Dec. 2, said analyst Trilby Lundberg.
   ``There could be some further price slippage,'' she said.
   The price reflects a stable wholesale market that saw little
fluctuation in prices despite continuing talks between members of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   ``OPEC discussions don't, in and of themselves, alter supply and
demand,'' Ms. Lundberg said. ``So as a result, the average wholesale
for the nation last week showed virtually no change at all.''
   The average retail price, which dropped 0.45 cents, includes all
grades of self- and full-serve gasoline, all taxes, and all cash and
credit sales.
   On Dec. 2, the average price at self-serve pumps for regular
unleaded gasoline was 89.80 cents a gallon; for premium unleaded
105.65; and for regular leaded 86.84 cents.
   The average price at full-serve pumps for regular unleaded
gasoline was 118.99 cents per gallon; for premium unleaded 130.08;
and regular leaded 115.76.
   On Nov. 18, the overall price was $1.0006.
   Although the OPEC meeting caused great movement in spot prices,
Ms. Lundberg said supply and demand will determine the market.
   ``Mainstream wholesale and spot markets leaped at the news that
OPEC had reached unity,'' she said. ``It's a very volatile
situation, but underlying all of this excitement and volatility is a
supply more abundant apparently than demand.''
   ``No matter what the importance of what they (OPEC) were saying,
that did not change existing supply and demand patterns,'' she said.
</TEXT>
